{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778697162268,"sessionID":"ses_1dd647e0effeZs5rb4D9DoknQl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_AqN74ENtVZtrSScL5Qq0v87i","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\n+title: \"Narrow EX/MEM control payload\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution payloads, but the EX/MEM execution register still carries the full decoded ctrl_t bundle after execute has consumed most of it. Branch, jump, operand-select, ALU-op, and AUIPC/LUI control bits are no longer needed once the EX result, write data, redirect, and RVFI pc_next have been produced. Trimming those cold bits at the EX/MEM boundary should reduce flop count, hold/reset muxing, and routing pressure on the memory, forwarding, and stall paths without changing CPI.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Introduce a compact post-EX control payload for EX/MEM and MEM-stage consumers containing only the bits still live after execute: mem_read, mem_write, mem_width, mem_sext, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Keep the full ctrl_t through ID/EX and inside EX where decode, branch, jump, ALU, AUIPC, and M-op decisions are still needed, then collapse to the compact control when registering EX/MEM. This is narrower than prior failed prediction/bypass/stall-hiding changes and differs from the regressed MEM/WB-only pruning by removing unused control before the hotter dmem, hazard, forwarding, and MEM/WB fanout cone.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a compact post-execute control struct and replace the EX/MEM execution payload's full ctrl_t field with that narrower type.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Map the full decoded control to the compact EX/MEM control at the execute boundary after branch, jump, AUIPC, M-op, and trap decisions are resolved.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use the compact EX/MEM control fields for memory request generation, misalignment trapping, load extension, and MEM/WB control propagation.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Update hazard and forwarding wiring to reference the compact EX/MEM control while preserving the NRET=1 RVFI port shape and retirement behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\n+title: \"Narrow EX/MEM control payload\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution payloads, but the EX/MEM execution register still carries the full decoded ctrl_t bundle after execute has consumed most of it. Branch, jump, operand-select, ALU-op, and AUIPC/LUI control bits are no longer needed once the EX result, write data, redirect, and RVFI pc_next have been produced. Trimming those cold bits at the EX/MEM boundary should reduce flop count, hold/reset muxing, and routing pressure on the memory, forwarding, and stall paths without changing CPI.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Introduce a compact post-EX control payload for EX/MEM and MEM-stage consumers containing only the bits still live after execute: mem_read, mem_write, mem_width, mem_sext, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Keep the full ctrl_t through ID/EX and inside EX where decode, branch, jump, ALU, AUIPC, and M-op decisions are still needed, then collapse to the compact control when registering EX/MEM. This is narrower than prior failed prediction/bypass/stall-hiding changes and differs from the regressed MEM/WB-only pruning by removing unused control before the hotter dmem, hazard, forwarding, and MEM/WB fanout cone.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a compact post-execute control struct and replace the EX/MEM execution payload's full ctrl_t field with that narrower type.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Map the full decoded control to the compact EX/MEM control at the execute boundary after branch, jump, AUIPC, M-op, and trap decisions are resolved.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use the compact EX/MEM control fields for memory request generation, misalignment trapping, load extension, and MEM/WB control propagation.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Update hazard and forwarding wiring to reference the compact EX/MEM control while preserving the NRET=1 RVFI port shape and retirement behavior.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5