{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778698737068,"sessionID":"ses_1dd4b964cffeq9qZa6LGSGNehP","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_EpP4936dS5q8iS7aaRKK1JdY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":32,"limit":6},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Narrow EX/MEM control payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution payloads, but the EX/MEM execution register still carries the full decoded ctrl_t bundle after execute has consumed most of it. Branch, jump, operand-select, ALU-op, and AUIPC/LUI control bits are no longer needed once the EX result, write data, redirect, and RVFI pc_next have been produced. Trimming those cold bits at the EX/MEM boundary should reduce flop count, hold/reset muxing, and routing pressure on the memory, forwarding, and stall paths without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution payloads, but the EX/MEM execution register still carries the full decoded ctrl_t bundle after execute has consumed most of it. Branch, jump, operand-select, ALU-op, and AUIPC/LUI control bits are no longer needed once the EX result, write data, redirect, and RVFI pc_next have been produced. Trimming those cold bits at the EX/MEM boundary should reduce flop count, hold/reset muxing, and routing pressure on the memory, forwarding, and stall paths without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Introduce a compact post-EX control payload for EX/MEM and MEM-stage consumers containing only the bits still live after execute: mem_read, mem_write, mem_width, mem_sext, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Keep the full ctrl_t through ID/EX and inside EX where decode, branch, jump, ALU, AUIPC, and M-op decisions are still needed, then collapse to the compact control when registering EX/MEM. This is narrower than prior failed prediction/bypass/stall-hiding changes and differs from the regressed MEM/WB-only pruning by removing unused control before the hotter dmem, hazard, forwarding, and MEM/WB fanout cone.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Handshake IFID register\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end feeds imem_data directly into decode, immediate generation,\\nregfile read-address selection, load-use hazard checks, and the ID/EX register in\\none cycle. Prior structural attempts that added prediction, bypassing, store\\nbuffering, or EX retiming regressed by adding hot mux/control paths. The earlier\\nIF/ID-register attempt broke because it lacked a real consume/valid handshake,\\nnot because the imem-to-decode retiming target was inherently invalid.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end feeds imem_data directly into decode, immediate generation,\\nregfile read-address selection, load-use hazard checks, and the ID/EX register in\\none cycle. Prior structural attempts that added prediction, bypassing, store\\nbuffering, or EX retiming regressed by adding hot mux/control paths. The earlier\\nIF/ID-register attempt broke because it lacked a real consume/valid handshake,\\nnot because the imem-to-decode retiming target was inherently invalid.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a proper registered IF/ID boundary with an explicit valid bit and ID consume\\nhandshake. IF captures a fetched instruction only when imem is ready and the IF/ID\\nslot is empty or ID is consuming it; ID consumes exactly one valid entry when the\\ndownstream ID/EX register is not held. Load-use, dmem, and M-unit stalls hold the\\nIF/ID entry without duplicating it, while EX redirects flush the registered entry\\nand update PC with redirect priority. This should remove the imem-data-to-decoder\\ncombinational path and improve Fmax, with only a small CPI risk and no change to\\nthe NRET=1 retirement/RVFI contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep the IF/ID bundle shape but treat it as a registered valid payload with explicit consume semantics documented for the implementation.\"},... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Fall-through redirect elision\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Every prior predictor that added fetch-side target arithmetic, tags, counters,\\nreturn-stack state, or predicted-PC metadata has regressed or broken this core.\\nThe current front end is already a static not-taken predictor for conditional\\nbranches, but EX still treats any resolved taken branch or jump as a redirect\\nand flushes younger stages even when the resolved target equals the fall-through\\nPC that fetch already predicted. Avoiding those false redirects is a predictor\\nrefinement with almost no new state or fetch-path cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Every prior predictor that added fetch-side target arithmetic, tags, counters,\\nreturn-stack state, or predicted-PC metadata has regressed or broken this core.\\nThe current front end is already a static not-taken predictor for conditional\\nbranches, but EX still treats any resolved taken branch or jump as a redirect\\nand flushes younger stages even when the resolved target equals the fall-through\\nPC that fetch already predicted. Avoiding those false redirects is a predictor\\nrefinement with almost no new state or fetch-path cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"In EX, compute the sequential fall-through PC as pc+4 and suppress redirect\\nwhen the resolved branch or jump target equals that fall-through address. The\\ninstruction should still retire with rvfi_pc_wdata equal to the architecturally\\nresolved target, but the front end does not need to flush because it has already\\nfetched the correct next instruction under the existing not-taken prediction.\\nThis keeps all prediction logic out of IF and avoids carrying predicted-next-PC\\nmetadata, while recovering bubbles from short JALs, degenerate branches, and\\nany compiler-generated control transfers whose target is the next instruction.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Class-bit M-op encoding\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent successful micro-optimizations improved fitness by removing always-active FPGA timing and routing pressure without adding new control-flow or memory machinery. The current EX stage still detects RV32M operations with eight separate alu_op equality comparisons, and that result feeds the M-unit start/busy path, redirect suppression, and EX/MEM bubble control. CoreMark rarely benefits from complex M-op detection logic being on this hot execute-control path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent successful micro-optimizations improved fitness by removing always-active FPGA timing and routing pressure without adding new control-flow or memory machinery. The current EX stage still detects RV32M operations with eight separate alu_op equality comparisons, and that result feeds the M-unit start/busy path, redirect suppression, and EX/MEM bubble control. CoreMark rarely benefits from complex M-op detection logic being on this hot execute-control path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Recode the internal ALU operation constants so every RV32M operation has alu_op[4]=1 while all ordinary RV32I operations keep alu_op[4]=0. Then replace the EX-stage is_m_op eight-way compare tree with a single in.valid && in.ctrl.alu_op[4] test. This preserves the decoder's legal-instruction checks, ALU and M-unit case behavior, RVFI retirement, and the existing one-cycle M-unit handshake, but should reduce LUT depth and fanout in the execute control path with no CPI cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Reassign ALU_MUL through ALU_REMU localparams into a contiguous high-bit class while leaving RV32I ALU ops below bit 4.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the explicit eight-operation is_m_op comparison with a single alu_op class-bit check.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delt... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Split ID/EX RVFI shadow\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The only clearly successful structural change in the recent bench history was\\nsplitting RVFI-only metadata away from the hot EX/MEM and MEM/WB datapath\\npayloads. The current ID/EX register still mixes execution-critical operands,\\nimmediate/control, and forwarding source numbers with RVFI-only instruction\\nbits and retirement reporting fields. A similarly narrow split at the decode\\nboundary targets register width, reset/hold muxing, and routing pressure\\nwithout adding predictors, memory ordering structures, bypass selects, or an\\nextra execute stage.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only clearly successful structural change in the recent bench history was\\nsplitting RVFI-only metadata away from the hot EX/MEM and MEM/WB datapath\\npayloads. The current ID/EX register still mixes execution-critical operands,\\nimmediate/control, and forwarding source numbers with RVFI-only instruction\\nbits and retirement reporting fields. A similarly narrow split at the decode\\nboundary targets register width, reset/hold muxing, and routing pressure\\nwithout adding predictors, memory ordering structures, bypass selects, or an\\nextra execute stage.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the single id_ex_t payload with a narrow execution payload and a\\nparallel ID/EX RVFI shadow payload. Keep the hot execution register limited\\nto PC, operands, immediate, rd, source register numbers needed by forwarding,\\ndecoded control, and valid; carry RVFI-only fields such as the original\\ninstruction and any retirement-only source metadata in a separate shadow\\nregister that follows the same stall and flush decisions. EX should consume\\nboth payloads and continue producing the existing split EX/MEM execution and\\nRVFI shadow outputs. This extends the proven RVFI-shadow structural pattern\\none stage earlier while preserving pipeline depth, redirect timing, load-use\\nbehavior, M-unit handshake, ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Guarded hot-loop predictor retry\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core have consistently regressed or broken\\nbecause target adders, tags, counters, RAS state, or predicted-PC metadata\\nlengthened hot fetch/decode/control paths. The only predictor already present\\nand essentially free is static sequential fetch, but CoreMark still pays two\\nbubbles on every taken loop-closing branch. The one predictor angle still\\nworth testing is a corrected, extremely small hot-loop predictor that avoids\\ntarget arithmetic in fetch and explicitly fixes the prior pc_fwd failure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core have consistently regressed or broken\\nbecause target adders, tags, counters, RAS state, or predicted-PC metadata\\nlengthened hot fetch/decode/control paths. The only predictor already present\\nand essentially free is static sequential fetch, but CoreMark still pays two\\nbubbles on every taken loop-closing branch. The one predictor angle still\\nworth testing is a corrected, extremely small hot-loop predictor that avoids\\ntarget arithmetic in fetch and explicitly fixes the prior pc_fwd failure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry EX-trained predictor for one taken backward conditional\\nbranch, but constrain the implementation around the last broken attempt's\\nfailure mode. IF only compares the current PC against one registered branch\\nPC and selects one registered target; it performs no instruction decode,\\ntarget addition, counters, or RAS work. Carry predicted_valid and\\npredicted_next_pc through IF/ID and ID/EX, and in EX suppress redirect only\\nwhen the branch is valid, actually taken, and its resolved target exactly\\nmatches predicted_next_pc. On predicted-taken loop exit, invalidate the entry\\nand redirect to pc+4 while reporting rvfi pc_next as pc+4 for that retiring\\nbranch. This narrow retry targets the most valuable CoreMark control hazard\\... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Narrow EX/MEM control payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution payloads, but the EX/MEM execution register still carries the full decoded ctrl_t bundle after execute has consumed most of it. Branch, jump, operand-select, ALU-op, and AUIPC/LUI control bits are no longer needed once the EX result, write data, redirect, and RVFI pc_next have been produced. Trimming those cold bits at the EX/MEM boundary should reduce flop count, hold/reset muxing, and routing pressure on the memory, forwarding, and stall paths without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution