{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778699818494,"sessionID":"ses_1dd3adde4ffep5jPLBvr070Y0N","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_DjMIF07KJ7xl7YNplpyMko7c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"micro_opt|category: micro_opt|\"category\": \"micro_opt\"|hyp-20260513-001-r14s0","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 14 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-5327bba\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-13T13:08:01.185076Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Multicycle RV32M arithmetic unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU computes every multiply and divide result combinationally in\\nthe EX stage, including signed and unsigned 64-bit products plus divider and\\nremainder operators. That wide arithmetic cone is a likely Fmax limiter on\\nTang Nano 20K, while CoreMark's hot path should not need single-cycle DIV/REM\\nthroughput. Trading rare M-extension latency for a shorter common EX critical\\npath should improve iterations/second through higher clock frequency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU computes every multiply and divide result combinationally in\\nthe EX stage, including signed and unsigned 64-bit products plus divider and\\nremainder operators. That wide arithmetic cone is a likely Fmax limiter on\\nTang Nano 20K, while CoreMark's hot path should not need single-cycle DIV/REM\\nthroughput. Trading rare M-extension latency for a shorter common EX critical\\npath should improve iterations/second through higher clock frequency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M operations out of the always-combinational ALU path behind a\\nsmall multicycle M-unit handshake in EX. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/branch/address\\noperations purely combinational, but when the decoded alu_op is MUL/DIV/REM,\\nhold ID/EX and EX/MEM until the iterative arithmetic result is ready, then\\nretire normally through the existing MEM/WB and RVFI path. This should remove\\ndivider and large multiplier logic from the ordinary EX-stage timing path;\\nthe added stalls only affect uncommon M instructions and should be outweighed\\nby improved Fmax on the FPGA fitness metric.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Restrict the combinational ALU to fast RV32I operations and expose only lightweight M-op selection or helper logic needed by the new M-unit.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a multicycl...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Simplify MEM load lane muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte-lane handling as explicit case muxes keyed by addr[1:0] instead of expressions like dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0] * 8) and mask << addr[1:0]. Keep the same misalignment trap behavior, RVFI aligned mem_addr reporting, replicated store data convention, and MEM/WB retirement boundary. This should reduce LUT depth and routing on the common load-data path while preserving the existing five-stage control flow and single-retire NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load-data shifts and shifted byte masks with explicit addr[1:0] case muxes for LB/LBU/LH/LHU/LW and store masks.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against the\\nraw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction, regardless of whether\\nthat instruction actually consumes those operands. For I-type immediates,\\nloads, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK, some of those fields are\\nimmediates or destination bits rather than true sources. Any accidental match\\nwith the preceding load rd inserts an unnecessary bubble, directly reducing\\nCoreMark iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against the\\nraw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction, regardless of whether\\nthat instruction actually consumes those operands. For I-type immediates,\\nloads, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK, some of those fields are\\nimmediates or destination bits rather than true sources. Any accidental match\\nwith the preceding load rd inserts an unnecessary bubble, directly reducing\\nCoreMark iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Make the load-use interlock source-aware by qualifying the rd comparisons with\\nsimple decoded uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 signals for the instruction currently in\\nIF/ID. Keep the existing one-cycle stall for real load consumers, but avoid\\nstalling on unused source fields such as OP-IMM rs2 bits, U/J-type operand\\nfields, and SYSTEM/FENCE encodings. This should improve CPI under CoreMark's\\nload-heavy code while adding only small opcode decode logic off the main ALU\\nand memory datapaths, so Fmax should be largely preserved.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive or wire IF/ID source-use qualifiers into the hazard unit without changing the NRET=1 top-level RVFI interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Source-qualified load interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\\nsource bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\\narchitecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\\ninstructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\\niterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\\nsource bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\\narchitecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\\ninstructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\\niterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny source-use decode for the IF/ID instruction and qualify the existing\\nload-use interlock with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. This is a narrower retry of the\\nearlier source-aware load-use idea: do not mask or reinterpret RVFI operand\\nreporting, and do not add MEM bypass selects or fetch prediction paths. The\\ncore should keep the one-cycle stall for true load consumers while avoiding\\nfalse stalls on OP-IMM rs2 fields, U/J-type immediates, FENCE, SYSTEM/EBREAK,\\nand other instructions that do not read both source registers.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive simple IF/ID uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 qualifiers from opcode/funct class and pass them only to the hazard unit.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate load-use rd comparisons with the source-use qualifiers while preserving existing dmem, imem, redirect, and M-unit stall priority.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive simple IF/ID use...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Drop regfile reset fanout\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a for-loop,\\nwhich forces reset muxing or reset routing onto the whole small RF array. After\\nthe M-unit split, remaining FPGA Fmax is likely limited by ordinary datapath\\nand control fanout rather than rare arithmetic. CoreMark initializes the state\\nit uses, x0 is already hardwired on reads, and RVFI correctness depends on\\nretired architectural behavior rather than power-on values of unused registers.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a for-loop,\\nwhich forces reset muxing or reset routing onto the whole small RF array. After\\nthe M-unit split, remaining FPGA Fmax is likely limited by ordinary datapath\\nand control fanout rather than rare arithmetic. CoreMark initializes the state\\nit uses, x0 is already hardwired on reads, and RVFI correctness depends on\\nretired architectural behavior rather than power-on values of unused registers.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the explicit reset clear from the integer register file and keep only\\nthe synchronous write path for nonzero destination registers. Reads of x0 stay\\nforced to zero, same-cycle write-first bypass stays unchanged, and reset of the\\npipeline control/valid bits still prevents spurious retirement after reset.\\nThis should reduce reset fanout and per-register muxing in a timing-sensitive,\\nalways-active block without changing CPI, branch behavior, memory behavior, or\\nthe NRET=1 RVFI interface. The change is deliberately narrower than prior\\nfailed micro-opts: it does not touch hazard detection, RVFI operand reporting,\\nMEM load extraction, or any front-end prediction path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the reset-time loop that clears all 32 registers while preser...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Prune dead EX/MEM branch metadata\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already won most of its fitness from removing broad\\ntiming/fanout costs, while recent attempts that add prediction, buffering,\\nbypassing, or memory-ordering control have regressed. The EX/MEM bundle still\\ncarries branch_taken and branch_target fields that are assigned every cycle\\nbut are not consumed by MEM, WB, RVFI, hazard, or forwarding logic. Those 33\\ndead flops and their input adders/mux routes sit in an always-active pipeline\\nboundary, so pruning them is a low-risk micro-optimization for LUT/FF count\\nand routing delay without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already won most of its fitness from removing broad\\ntiming/fanout costs, while recent attempts that add prediction, buffering,\\nbypassing, or memory-ordering control have regressed. The EX/MEM bundle still\\ncarries branch_taken and branch_target fields that are assigned every cycle\\nbut are not consumed by MEM, WB, RVFI, hazard, or forwarding logic. Those 33\\ndead flops and their input adders/mux routes sit in an always-active pipeline\\nboundary, so pruning them is a low-risk micro-optimization for LUT/FF count\\nand routing delay without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t and stop\\nregistering them in ex_stage. Keep redirect and pc_next computation exactly as\\nthey are today, because pc_next is the RVFI-visible resolved next PC and the\\nredirect output is still the only live control-flow signal. This should trim\\ndead sequential state and reduce EX-stage fanout/routing pressure while\\npreserving the NRET=1 RVFI contract, trap behavior, memory behavior, and all\\nexisting stall/flush priorities.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove unused branch_taken and...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative M divider\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The largest proven fitness gain for this core came from moving RV32M arithmetic\\nout of the ordinary EX ALU path, but the current m_unit still contains wide\\ncombinational DIV/REM operators behind a one-cycle result register. Even if\\nthose operations are rare in CoreMark, the FPGA still has to place and time\\nthe divider/remainder cone, so it can cap Fmax or perturb routing for the hot\\nRV32I pipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The largest proven fitness gain for this core came from moving RV32M arithmetic\\nout of the ordinary EX ALU path, but the current m_unit still contains wide\\ncombinational DIV/REM operators behind a one-cycle result register. Even if\\nthose operations are rare in CoreMark, the FPGA still has to place and time\\nthe divider/remainder cone, so it can cap Fmax or perturb routing for the hot\\nRV32I pipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the one-cycle DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU implementation in m_unit with a small\\niterative restoring divider that runs only after a divide or remainder starts.\\nKeep MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU on the existing short registered path so any\\nmultiply use does not pay a 32-cycle penalty, and keep the existing EX-stage\\nhold/valid handshake as the only pipeline interface. This should remove the\\nexpensive combinational divider/remainder logic from the FPGA timing closure\\nproblem while adding CPI only for uncommon divide/remainder instructions.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/m_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with an iterative signed/unsigned divider state machine while preserving ALTOPS behavior under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Adjust the existing M-unit busy/valid handshake only as needed so EX holds until multi-cycle DIV/REM completion and still clears completed results exactly once.\"}]}, \"expec...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Share M-unit multiplier hardware\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already removed RV32M arithmetic from the ordinary EX\\nALU path, but m_unit still builds three separate 64-bit multiplier products\\nin parallel for MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU signedness variants. CoreMark uses\\nM operations rarely enough that throughput beyond the existing one-cycle\\nregistered M-unit is not the main limiter, while the extra DSP/LUT/routing\\npressure can still depress FPGA Fmax or perturb placement of the hot RV32I\\npipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already removed RV32M arithmetic from the ordinary EX\\nALU path, but m_unit still builds three separate 64-bit multiplier products\\nin parallel for MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU signedness variants. CoreMark uses\\nM operations rarely enough that throughput beyond the existing one-cycle\\nregistered M-unit is not the main limiter, while the extra DSP/LUT/routing\\npressure can still depress FPGA Fmax or perturb placement of the hot RV32I\\npipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the parallel signed-signed, unsigned-unsigned, and signed-unsigned\\nproduct generation in m_unit with one shared signed multiplier fed by\\nsign/zero-extended operands selected from the M opcode. MUL can take the low\\nhalf of the same product because low 32 bits are independent of operand\\nsignedness; MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU select the high half with the appropriate\\noperand extension. Keep the existing start/valid/clear handshake, one-cycle\\nM latency, DIV/REM behavior, and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions unchanged.\\nThis should trim multiplier area and routing without adding CPI, front-end\\nprediction logic, memory ordering state, or any RVFI-visible behavior change.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/m_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Use a single sign-controlled widened multiplier for MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU while pres...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Narrow MEM/WB control state\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization wins came from removing always-present FPGA timing\\nand routing pressure, while attempts that added prediction, bypassing, or\\nstall-hiding control usually regressed. The current MEM/WB register still\\ncarries the full decode control bundle even though the writeback and RVFI\\nretirement logic only consume a few bits after the MEM stage. Pruning that\\ncold control state should reduce flop count, muxing, and routing without\\nchanging CoreMark CPI or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization wins came from removing always-present FPGA timing\\nand routing pressure, while attempts that added prediction, bypassing, or\\nstall-hiding control usually regressed. The current MEM/WB register still\\ncarries the full decode control bundle even though the writeback and RVFI\\nretirement logic only consume a few bits after the MEM stage. Pruning that\\ncold control state should reduce flop count, muxing, and routing without\\nchanging CoreMark CPI or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the full ctrl_t field in mem_wb_t with a narrow retirement/writeback\\ncontrol subset containing only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Keep\\nthe existing full ctrl_t through ID/EX and EX/MEM, because the execute and\\nmemory stages still need branch, memory width, sign-extension, and M-op\\ncontrols. In mem_stage, collapse ctrl_with_trap into the narrow MEM/WB\\nfields after misalignment handling, and update wb_stage and core RVFI trap\\nreferences to use the narrow fields. This should trim unused MEM/WB control\\nflops and fanout while preserving all memory masks/data, load results,\\nwriteback behavior, RVFI order, and trap reporting.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce a narrow M...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Prune unused LUI control bit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent wins came from removing always-present arithmetic, reset, and RVFI\\nrouting pressure, while broader CPI-oriented changes and control prediction\\nusually regressed. The current control bundle still carries an is_lui bit\\nthrough decode and every pipeline stage even though LUI execution is already\\nfully encoded by alu_op=ALU_LUI and alu_src=1. That unused bit adds one more\\ndecoded signal, pipeline flop, reset/hold mux input, and routing load across\\nhot stage boundaries without contributing to architectural behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent wins came from removing always-present arithmetic, reset, and RVFI\\nrouting pressure, while broader CPI-oriented changes and control prediction\\nusually regressed. The current control bundle still carries an is_lui bit\\nthrough decode and every pipeline stage even though LUI execution is already\\nfully encoded by alu_op=ALU_LUI and alu_src=1. That unused bit adds one more\\ndecoded signal, pipeline flop, reset/hold mux input, and routing load across\\nhot stage boundaries without contributing to architectural behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the redundant is_lui signal from the decoder interface and ctrl_t,\\nand delete the corresponding ID-stage temporary and bundle assignment. Keep\\nLUI behavior unchanged by continuing to set alu_op=ALU_LUI, alu_src=1, and\\nreg_write=1 in the existing validated LUI decode arm. This is a narrow\\nno-CPI micro-optimization that should slightly reduce control-bundle width,\\nregister enables, reset/hold muxing, and decode-to-EX routing pressure while\\npreserving the NRET=1 RVFI contract, trap discipline, memory behavior, and\\nall existing stall/forwarding logic.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused is_lui field from ctrl_t so it no longer propagates throug...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Narrow EX/MEM control payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution payloads, but the EX/MEM execution register still carries the full decoded ctrl_t bundle after execute has consumed most of it. Branch, jump, operand-select, ALU-op, and AUIPC/LUI control bits are no longer needed once the EX result, write data, redirect, and RVFI pc_next have been produced. Trimming those cold bits at the EX/MEM boundary should reduce flop count, hold/reset muxing, and routing pressure on the memory, forwarding, and stall paths without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from splitting RVFI shadow metadata away from hot execution payloads, but the EX/MEM execution register still carries the full decoded ctrl_t bundle after execute has consumed most of it. Branch, jump, operand-select, ALU-op, and AUIPC/LUI control bits are no longer needed once the EX result, write data, redirect, and RVFI pc_next have been produced. Trimming those cold bits at the EX/MEM boundary should reduce flop count, hold/reset muxing, and routing pressure on the memory, forwarding, and stall paths without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Introduce a compact post-EX control payload for EX/MEM and MEM-stage consumers containing only the bits still live after execute: mem_read, mem_write, mem_width, mem_sext, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Keep the full ctrl_t through ID/EX and inside EX where decode, branch, jump, ALU, AUIPC, and M-op decisions are still needed, then collapse to the compact control when registering EX/MEM. This is narrower than prior failed prediction/bypass/stall-hiding changes and differs from the regressed MEM/WB-only pruning by removing unused control before the hotter dmem, hazard, forwarding, and MEM/WB fanout cone.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Class-bit M-op encoding\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent successful micro-optimizations improved fitness by removing always-active FPGA timing and routing pressure without adding new control-flow or memory machinery. The current EX stage still detects RV32M operations with eight separate alu_op equality comparisons, and that result feeds the M-unit start/busy path, redirect suppression, and EX/MEM bubble control. CoreMark rarely benefits from complex M-op detection logic being on this hot execute-control path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent successful micro-optimizations improved fitness by removing always-active FPGA timing and routing pressure without adding new control-flow or memory machinery. The current EX stage still detects RV32M operations with eight separate alu_op equality comparisons, and that result feeds the M-unit start/busy path, redirect suppression, and EX/MEM bubble control. CoreMark rarely benefits from complex M-op detection logic being on this hot execute-control path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Recode the internal ALU operation constants so every RV32M operation has alu_op[4]=1 while all ordinary RV32I operations keep alu_op[4]=0. Then replace the EX-stage is_m_op eight-way compare tree with a single in.valid && in.ctrl.alu_op[4] test. This preserves the decoder's legal-instruction checks, ALU and M-unit case behavior, RVFI retirement, and the existing one-cycle M-unit handshake, but should reduce LUT depth and fanout in the execute control path with no CPI cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Reassign ALU_MUL through ALU_REMU localparams into a contiguous high-bit class while leaving RV32I ALU ops below bit 4.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the explicit eight-operation is_m_op comparison with a single alu_op class-bit check.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delt...\n  Line 38: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"Prune redundant LUI control\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest bench-core results have come from removing always-active FPGA\\nrouting pressure without adding new prediction, bypass, memory ordering, or\\nretiming machinery. The current control bundle still carries an is_lui bit\\nfrom decode through ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB even though no live execute,\\nmemory, writeback, hazard, or RVFI logic consumes it. LUI behavior is already\\nfully represented by alu_op=ALU_LUI, alu_src=1, and reg_write=1.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest bench-core results have come from removing always-active FPGA\\nrouting pressure without adding new prediction, bypass, memory ordering, or\\nretiming machinery. The current control bundle still carries an is_lui bit\\nfrom decode through ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB even though no live execute,\\nmemory, writeback, hazard, or RVFI logic consumes it. LUI behavior is already\\nfully represented by alu_op=ALU_LUI, alu_src=1, and reg_write=1.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the redundant is_lui signal from ctrl_t and from the decoder and ID\\nstage wiring, leaving the existing LUI decode arm to set ALU_LUI, alu_src,\\nand reg_write exactly as before. This should slightly reduce control-bundle\\nwidth, pipeline register muxing, and decode-to-execute routing fanout with no\\nCPI cost and no change to the NRET=1 top-level RVFI contract. The change is\\nintentionally smaller than the regressed control-payload splits and avoids\\nall front-end predictor or memory-bypass paths that have repeatedly lost\\nfitness on this FPGA.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused is_lui field from ctrl_t so it no longer propagates through pipeline payloads.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/decoder.sv\", \"description\": \"Drop the is_lui output and keep the validated LUI arm encoded through ALU_LUI, alu_src, and reg_write.\"},...","metadata":{"matches":14,"truncated":false},"title":"micro_opt|category: micro_opt|\"category\": \"micro_opt\"|hyp-20260513-001-r14s0","time":{"start":1778699818486,"end":1778699818493}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0fc1f8544fd94f88016a04ce2a3d68819888d7acc7d5f83492"}},"id":"prt_e22c555e4001Vsn5clPE36T6fq","sessionID":"ses_1dd3adde4ffep5jPLBvr070Y0N","messageID":"msg_e22c52273001KQeLK0QIp7jPyP"}}
