{"type":"text","timestamp":1778699841707,"sessionID":"ses_1dd3adde4ffep5jPLBvr070Y0N","part":{"id":"prt_e22c5a869001bfGl2OAEmpcW2i","messageID":"msg_e22c55696001X05M25fI2qbqN7","sessionID":"ses_1dd3adde4ffep5jPLBvr070Y0N","type":"text","text":"The prior `micro_opt` wins cluster around removing arithmetic/reset/RVFI routing pressure, while later control-bundle pruning and predictor-like changes often regressed. I’m choosing a narrow M-unit retiming hypothesis because it targets remaining wide arithmetic timing without introducing predictor, memory-ordering, or front-end state.","time":{"start":1778699839593,"end":1778699841706},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0d50342d986deeaf016a04ce3f7d9c8198ac021fc4fe8cf016","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778699857450,"sessionID":"ses_1dd3adde4ffep5jPLBvr070Y0N","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_E0icir1PbSTPh6dgZBRMKRhh","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r14s0\n+title: \"Retimed M-unit operand stage\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The largest proven bench-core gains came from keeping rare RV32M arithmetic off the ordinary RV32I execute path, and the smaller multiplier-sharing win suggests M-unit placement and timing still matter on the Tang Nano 20K. The current M unit still evaluates multiply/divide/remainder results directly from EX operands into the result register on the start edge, so a wide arithmetic cone remains a possible global Fmax limiter even though CoreMark rarely needs M-op throughput.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a registered operand/opcode stage inside m_unit so start only captures the selected RV32M operation and operands, then compute and register the arithmetic result on the following cycle. Adjust the existing EX-stage hold logic to wait on the M unit's valid output rather than assuming exactly one bubble. This trades one extra cycle on rare MUL/DIV/REM instructions for a shorter start-to-register timing path, without touching branch prediction, memory bypassing, load-use behavior, RVFI fields, or the NRET=1 top-level interface.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/m_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Insert registered op/a/b operands ahead of the existing RV32M arithmetic and produce valid one cycle later while preserving RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS results.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use the M-unit busy/valid handshake to hold the in-flight M instruction until the retimed result is available, preserving redirect suppression and RVFI operand reporting.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,15 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r14s0\n+title: \"Retimed M-unit operand stage\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The largest proven bench-core gains came from keeping rare RV32M arithmetic off the ordinary RV32I execute path, and the smaller multiplier-sharing win suggests M-unit placement and timing still matter on the Tang Nano 20K. The current M unit still evaluates multiply/divide/remainder results directly from EX operands into the result register on the start edge, so a wide arithmetic cone remains a possible global Fmax limiter even though CoreMark rarely needs M-op throughput.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a registered operand/opcode stage inside m_unit so start only captures the selected RV32M operation and operands, then compute and register the arithmetic result on the following cycle. Adjust the existing EX-stage hold logic to wait on the M unit's valid output rather than assuming exactly one bubble. This trades one extra cycle on rare MUL/DIV/REM instructions for a shorter start-to-register timing path, without touching branch prediction, memory bypassing, load-use behavior, RVFI fields, or the NRET=1 top-level interface.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/m_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Insert registered op/a/b operands ahead of the existing RV32M arithmetic and produce valid one cycle later while preserving RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS results.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use the M-unit busy/valid handshake to hold the in-flight M instruction until the retimed result is available, preserving redirect suppression and RVFI operand reporting.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,15 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r14s0\n+title: \"Retimed M-unit operand stage\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The largest proven bench-core gains came from keeping rare RV32M arithmetic off the ordinary RV32I execute path, and the smaller multiplier-sharing win suggests M-unit placement and timing still matter on the Tang Nano 20K. The current M unit still evaluates multiply/divide/remainder results directly from EX operands into the result register on the start edge, so a wide arithmetic cone remains a possible global Fmax limiter even though CoreMark rarely needs M-op throughput.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a registered operand/opcode stage inside m_unit so start only captures the selected RV32M operation and operands, then compute and register the arithmetic result on the following cycle. Adjust the existing EX-stage hold logic to wait on the M unit's valid output rather than assuming exactly one bubble. This trades one extra cycle on rare MUL/DIV/REM instructions for a shorter start-to-register timing path, without touching branch prediction, memory bypassing, load-use behavior, RVFI fields, or the NRET=1 top-level interface.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/m_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Insert registered op/a/b operands ahead of the existing RV32M arithmetic and produce valid one cycle later while preserving RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS results.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use the M-unit busy/valid handshake to hold the in-flight M instruction until the retimed result is available, preserving redirect suppression and RVFI operand reporting.\"\n","additions":15,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r14s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778699857446,"end":1778699857449}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0d50342d986deeaf016a04ce43cd648198a6d945b862197bd3"}},"id":"prt_e22c5b946001tAoRx1gnLPKeQf","sessionID":"ses_1dd3adde4ffep5jPLBvr070Y0N","messageID":"msg_e22c55696001X05M25fI2qbqN7"}}
