{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778700542836,"sessionID":"ses_1dd308545ffeS2tbmWRdSb0axR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_1jqbXNIzJuYLieCvVLfZYLe7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r15s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r15s0\n+title: \"Range-test M-op detect\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent bench results favor very small micro-optimizations that remove always-active FPGA logic without adding predictors, bypass paths, deeper pipeline stages, or new memory control. The current EX stage still identifies RV32M instructions with eight explicit alu_op equality comparisons, and that signal fans into M-unit start, EX bubble insertion, redirect suppression, and global stall control. A narrower decode expression can reduce LUT depth and routing pressure in execute control while keeping the existing opcode encodings and M-unit protocol intact.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the eight-way RV32M equality tree in ex_stage with a compact range test over the existing contiguous ALU_MUL through ALU_REMU localparam values. Unlike the prior class-bit recoding attempt, this does not perturb alu_op encodings, decoder packing, ALU cases, or M-unit cases; it only changes the local is_m_op predicate implementation. The core should retain identical CPI, RVFI retirement, trap behavior, and one-cycle M-unit handshake, with a small chance of improving Fmax by shortening execute control logic.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 1\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the explicit eight-operation is_m_op equality chain with a compact range check against the existing contiguous ALU_MUL..ALU_REMU values, preserving all M-unit handshake and redirect behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r15s0.yaml","metadata":{"di