{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778682616484,"sessionID":"ses_1de422e1bffe6wzHLoYYx6xJoX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Ej4g4rjsP6QpvKVw42rYGEpo","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Source-qualified load interlock\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\n+  source bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\n+  architecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\n+  instructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\n+  iterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny source-use decode for the IF/ID instruction and qualify the existing\n+  load-use interlock with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. This is a narrower retry of the\n+  earlier source-aware load-use idea: do not mask or reinterpret RVFI operand\n+  reporting, and do not add MEM bypass selects or fetch prediction paths. The\n+  core should keep the one-cycle stall for true load consumers while avoiding\n+  false stalls on OP-IMM rs2 fields, U/J-type immediates, FENCE, SYSTEM/EBREAK,\n+  and other instructions that do not read both source registers.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Derive simple IF/ID uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 qualifiers from opcode/funct class and pass them only to the hazard unit.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Gate load-use rd comparisons with the source-use qualifiers while preserving existing dmem, imem, redirect, and M-unit stall priority.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Source-qualified load interlock\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\n+  source bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\n+  architecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\n+  instructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\n+  iterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny source-use decode for the IF/ID instruction and qualify the existing\n+  load-use interlock with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. This is a narrower retry of the\n+  earlier source-aware load-use idea: do not mask or reinterpret RVFI operand\n+  reporting, and do not add MEM bypass selects or fetch prediction paths. The\n+  core should keep the one-cycle stall for true load consumers while avoiding\n+  false stalls on OP-IMM rs2 fields, U/J-type immediates, FENCE, SYSTEM/EBREAK,\n+  and other instructions that do not read both source registers.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Derive simple IF/ID uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 qualifiers from opcode/funct class and pass them only to the hazard unit.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Gate load-use rd comparisons with the source-use qualifiers while preserving existing dmem, imem, redirect, and M-unit stall priority.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Source-qualified load interlock\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\n+  source bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\n+  architecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\n+  instructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\n+  iterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny source-use decode for the IF/ID instruction and qualify the existing\n+  load-use interlock with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. This is a narrower retry of the\n+  earlier source-aware load-use idea: do not mask or reinterpret RVFI operand\n+  reporting, and do not add MEM bypass selects or fetch prediction paths. The\n+  core should keep the one-cycle stall for true load consumers while avoiding\n+  false stalls on OP-IMM rs2 fields, U/J-type immediates, FENCE, SYSTEM/EBREAK,\n+  and other instructions that do not read both source registers.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confide