{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684901610,"sessionID":"ses_1de1f1abdffep9rf1EOtsrxmOX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_NbNpSyPKUCmpvDNf7tLDnwwx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Drop regfile reset fanout\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a for-loop,\n+  which forces reset muxing or reset routing onto the whole small RF array. After\n+  the M-unit split, remaining FPGA Fmax is likely limited by ordinary datapath\n+  and control fanout rather than rare arithmetic. CoreMark initializes the state\n+  it uses, x0 is already hardwired on reads, and RVFI correctness depends on\n+  retired architectural behavior rather than power-on values of unused registers.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the explicit reset clear from the integer register file and keep only\n+  the synchronous write path for nonzero destination registers. Reads of x0 stay\n+  forced to zero, same-cycle write-first bypass stays unchanged, and reset of the\n+  pipeline control/valid bits still prevents spurious retirement after reset.\n+  This should reduce reset fanout and per-register muxing in a timing-sensitive,\n+  always-active block without changing CPI, branch behavior, memory behavior, or\n+  the NRET=1 RVFI interface. The change is deliberately narrower than prior\n+  failed micro-opts: it does not touch hazard detection, RVFI operand reporting,\n+  MEM load extraction, or any front-end prediction path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the reset-time loop that clears all 32 registers while preserving x0 reads, nonzero writes, and write-first same-cycle bypass semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Drop regfile reset fanout\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a for-loop,\n+  which forces reset muxing or reset routing onto the whole small RF array. After\n+  the M-unit split, remaining FPGA Fmax is likely limited by ordinary datapath\n+  and control fanout rather than rare arithmetic. CoreMark initializes the state\n+  it uses, x0 is already hardwired on reads, and RVFI correctness depends on\n+  retired architectural behavior rather than power-on values of unused registers.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the explicit reset clear from the integer register file and keep only\n+  the synchronous write path for nonzero destination registers. Reads of x0 stay\n+  forced to zero, same-cycle write-first bypass stays unchanged, and reset of the\n+  pipeline control/valid bits still prevents spurious retirement after reset.\n+  This should reduce reset fanout and per-register muxing in a timing-sensitive,\n+  always-active block without changing CPI, branch behavior, memory behavior, or\n+  the NRET=1 RVFI interface. The change is deliberately narrower than prior\n+  failed micro-opts: it does not touch hazard detection, RVFI operand reporting,\n+  MEM load extraction, or any front-end prediction path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the reset-time loop that clears all 32 registers while preserving x0 reads, nonzero writes, and write-first same-cycle bypass semantics.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Drop regfile reset fanout\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a for-loop,\n+  which forces reset muxing or reset routing onto the whole small RF array. After\n+  the M-unit split, remaining FPGA Fmax is likely limited by ordinary datapath\n+  and control fanout rather than rare arithmetic. CoreMark initializes the state\n+  it uses, x0 is already hardwired on reads, and RVFI correctness depends on\n+  retired architectural behavior rather than power-on values of unused registers.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the explicit reset clear from the integer register file and keep only\n+  the synchronous write path for nonzero destination registers. Reads of x0 stay\n+  forced to zero, same-cycle write-first bypass stays unchanged, and reset of the\n+  pipeline control/valid bits still prevents spurious retirement after reset.\n+  This should reduce reset fanout and per-register muxing in a timing-sensitive,\n+  always-active block without changing CPI, branch behavior, memory behavior, or\n+  the NRET=1 RVFI interface. The change is deliberately narrower than prior\n+  failed micro-opts: it does not touch hazard detection, RVFI operand reporting,\n+  MEM load extraction, or any front-end prediction path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the reset-time loop that clears all 32 registers while preserving x0 reads, nonzero writes, and write-first same-cycle bypass semantics.\"\n","additions":26,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778684901604,"end":1778684901609}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0757bcb66e77d264016a0493d4c038819987dc98c2107e567e"}},"id":"prt_e21e1777b001Q7mkRKdGQ6Mu1l","sessionID":"ses_1de1f1abdffep9rf1EOtsrxmOX","messageID":"msg_e21e16a73001eLvldbKTroNtrt"}}
