{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778689161457,"sessionID":"ses_1ddde3f62ffe7ptYFGvwU9A50r","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_pRfYiP5EF9L2L1lmMi0j74FC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r7s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r7s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\n2: title: \"Iterative M divider\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The largest proven fitness gain for this core came from moving RV32M arithmetic\n6:   out of the ordinary EX ALU path, but the current m_unit still contains wide\n7:   combinational DIV/REM operators behind a one-cycle result register. Even if\n8:   those operations are rare in CoreMark, the FPGA still has to place and time\n9:   the divider/remainder cone, so it can cap Fmax or perturb routing for the hot\n10:   RV32I pipeline.\n11: hypothesis: |\n12:   Replace the one-cycle DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU implementation in m_unit with a small\n13:   iterative restoring divider that runs only after a divide or remainder starts.\n14:   Keep MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU on the existing short registered path so any\n15:   multiply use does not pay a 32-cycle penalty, and keep the existing EX-stage\n16:   hold/valid handshake as the only pipeline interface. This should remove the\n17:   expensive combinational divider/remainder logic from the FPGA timing closure\n18:   problem while adding CPI only for uncommon divide/remainder instructions.\n19: expected_impact:\n20:   fitness_delta_pct: 4\n21:   confidence: medium\n22: changes:\n23:   - file: rtl/m_unit.sv\n24:     description: \"Implement DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with an iterative signed/unsigned divider state machine while preserving ALTOPS behavior under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS.\"\n25:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n26:     description: \"Adjust the existing M-unit busy/valid handshake only as needed so EX holds until multi-cycle DIV/REM completion and still clears completed results exactly once.\"\n\n(End of file - total 26 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\ntitle: \"Iterative M divider\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The largest proven fitness gain for this core came from moving RV32M arithmetic\n  out of the ordinary EX ALU path, but the current m_unit still contains wide\n  combinational DIV/REM operators behind a one-cycle result register. Even if\n  those operations are rare in CoreMark, the FPGA still has to place and time\n  the divider/remainder cone, so it can cap Fmax or perturb routing for the hot\n  RV32I pipeline.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the one-cycle DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU implementation in m_unit with a small\n  iterative restoring divider that runs only after a divide or remainder starts.\n  Keep MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU on the existing short registered path so any\n  multiply use does not pay a 32-cycle penalty, and keep the existing EX-stage\n  hold/valid handshake as the only pipeline interface. This should remove the\n  expensive combinational divider/remainder logic from the FPGA timing closure\n  problem while adding CPI only for uncommon divide/remainder instructions.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r7s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778689161445,"end":1778689161456}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_001d041d257ada2a016a04a4880778819b9c5baf60d7599a3c"}},"id":"prt_e2222b4010013zfdVpZ2uKjy0B","sessionID":"ses_1ddde3f62ffe7ptYFGvwU9A50r","messageID":"msg_e22229c82001e6cBoxapHfl6CZ"}}
