{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778695238059,"sessionID":"ses_1dd80c37dffeA0edlSklrIPTbJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_rZHyeMg5mqrdgTKXspD13JVx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r1s0 (improvement, +32.85%): Moving RV32M multiply/divide out of the combinational EX ALU behind a multicycle handshake can substantially improve FPGA fitness because CoreMark rarely needs M-op throughput while the removed arithmetic cone dominates Fmax.\n2: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Moving branch/JALR resolution into ID needs exhaustive operand-valid stalling and forwarding for decode-stage compares/base operands; stale early redirects can let wrong-path state reach writeback, which riscv-formal's reg check catches.\n3: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (regression, +21.76%): IF-stage BTFNT/JAL prediction can regress CoreMark when instruction-bit immediate decode and target adders sit directly on the fetch PC path, so front-end bubble savings must be weighed against Fmax-critical next-PC logic.\n4: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, -1.92%): Replacing MEM-stage variable shifts with explicit byte/halfword lane case muxes did not help FPGA fitness, suggesting the synthesizer already maps these narrow shifts well and the added mux/control structure can slightly worsen routing or LUT packing.\n5: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r2s1 (regression, -7.79%): A two-entry IF skid buffer did not pay for CoreMark's random imem stalls; the added fetch-valid/control and redirect-flush machinery can cost more FPGA fitness than the front-end bubbles it hides.\n6: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 (regression, -44.37%): A tiny IF return-address stack can still badly hurt FPGA fitness when canonical-return detection, RAS top muxing, and predicted-PC metadata outweigh the CoreMark return bubbles it removes.\n7: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (broken, n/a): Keep source-aware load-use interlocks separate from RVFI operand reporting changes; masking unused rs fields can break cosim's retire trace even when the intended stall reduction logic is local to hazard_unit.\n8: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -14.30%): MEM-to-EX load bypass can lose FPGA fitness when dmem-ready gating, load extraction, and an extra EX operand forwarding select lengthen the critical path more than CoreMark benefits from removing one-cycle load-use bubbles.\n9: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -20.54%): Even decode-stage JAL prediction can regress when the early_redirect priority path, target adder, and predicted-PC metadata still add enough IF/ID/EX control cost to outweigh saving CoreMark's unconditional-jump bubble.\n10: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): A registered IF/ID boundary must pair imem backpressure with an ID consume/valid handshake; holding a valid IF/ID entry while ID keeps advancing can duplicate instructions during CoreMark stalls.\n11: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -9.29%): Even a resolved-target BTB can lose FPGA fitness when IF-side tag/valid/counter arrays, target muxing, and predicted-PC metadata lengthen the next-PC path more than CoreMark benefits from avoiding loop redirect bubbles.\n12: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (improvement, +1.93%): Dropping reset clears from the integer register file can improve FPGA fitness because pipeline-valid reset and x0 read forcing preserve architectural behavior while avoiding reset fanout and per-register muxing in an always-active datapath block.\n13: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r5s1 (regression, -6.89%): A one-entry ordered store buffer can lose CoreMark fitness when store-order interlocks, MMIO/trap classification, and dmem muxing add more MEM/control-path cost than random store-stall overlap recovers.\n14: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -61.05%): Even a single-entry loop predictor can badly regress when predicted-PC metadata, IF PC/tag compare muxing, and EX mismatch redirect logic lengthen critical control paths more than repeated CoreMark loop-branch bubble removal helps.\n15: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (regression, -2.40%): Pruning unused EX/MEM branch_taken/branch_target metadata did not improve FPGA fitness, suggesting these dead-looking pipeline fields were not on the binding path or were already optimized well enough that layout perturbation outweighed the small flop reduction.\n16: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (regression, -88.09%): Splitting EX with an EX1 operand register can destroy CoreMark fitness when it delays branch/JALR redirects and forces broad dependent-ALU interlocks, so operand-cone retiming must preserve bypass/redirect latency to pay off.\n17: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (regression, -48.05%): A JAL-only single-entry target predictor still regressed without fetch-side immediate decode because the IF PC compare/target mux, predicted-PC pipeline fields, and EX mismatch redirect logic outweighed CoreMark's repeated unconditional-jump bubble savings.\n18: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (regression, -53.28%): Replacing cold RV32M DIV/REM combinational operators with an iterative divider can severely regress CoreMark when the busy/start handshake, divider state, and 32-cycle latency perturb the hot pipeline more than removing the rarely used divide cone helps Fmax.\n19: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (broken, n/a): Registering dmem backpressure needs a real ready/valid or skid boundary at MEM; a lone pending/wait bit can hide the first stalled cycle from upstream control and let younger CoreMark memory-state updates be dropped or reordered.\n20: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r8s0 (improvement, +2.79%): Sharing one sign/zero-extended M-unit multiplier across MULH signedness variants can improve FPGA fitness because CoreMark rarely needs M throughput and parallel 64-bit products add DSP/LUT routing pressure.\n21: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r8s1 (regression, -0.33%): Preselecting MEM/WB writeback data inside mem_stage did not improve fitness, suggesting the load-vs-ALU writeback mux is not a binding FPGA path and adding another pipeline field can slightly worsen packing/routing.\n22: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r8s2 (regression, +1.88%): Moving backward-branch prediction from IF to ID still regressed because the ID target adder, redirect/stall arbitration, predicted-PC metadata, and EX mispredict compare/control outweighed CoreMark loop-bubble savings.\n\n(End of file - total 22 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r1s0 (improvement, +32.85%): Moving RV32M multiply/divide out of the combinational EX ALU behind a multicycle handshake can substantially improve FPGA fitness because CoreMark rarely needs M-op throughput while the removed arithmetic cone dominates Fmax.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Moving branch/JALR resolution into ID needs exhaustive operand-valid stalling and forwarding for decode-stage compares/base operands; stale early redirects can let wrong-path state reach writeback, which riscv-formal's reg check catches.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (regression, +21.76%): IF-stage BTFNT/JAL prediction can regress CoreMark when instruction-bit immediate decode and target adders sit directly on the fetch PC path, so front-end bubble savings must be weighed against Fmax-critical next-PC logic.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, -1.92%): Replacing MEM-stage variable shifts with explicit byte/halfword lane case muxes did not help FPGA fitness, suggesting the synthesizer already maps these narrow shifts well and the added mux/control structure can slightly worsen routing or LUT packing.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r2s1 (regression, -7.79%): A two-entry IF skid buffer did not pay for CoreMark's random imem stalls; the added fetch-valid/control and redirect-flush machinery can cost more FPGA fitness than the front-end bubbles it hides.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 (regression, -44.37%): A tiny IF return-address stack can still badly hurt FPGA fitness when canonical-return detection, RAS top muxing, and predicted-PC metadata outweigh the CoreMark return bubbles it removes.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (broken, n/a): Keep source-aware load-use interlocks separate from RVFI operand reporting changes; masking unused rs fields can break cosim's retire trace even when the intended stall reduction logic is local to hazard_unit.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -14.30%): MEM-to-EX load bypass can lose FPGA fitness when dmem-ready gating, load extraction, and an extra EX operand forwarding select lengthen the critical path more than CoreMark benefits from removing one-cycle load-use bubbles.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -20.54%): Even decode-stage JAL prediction can regress when the early_redirect priority path, target adder, and predicted-PC metadata still add enough IF/ID/EX control cost to outweigh saving CoreMark's unconditional-jump bubble.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): A registered IF/ID boundary must pair imem backpressure with an ID consume/valid handshake; holding a valid IF/ID entry while ID keeps advancing can duplicate instructions during CoreMark stalls.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -9.29%): Even a resolved-target BTB can lose FPGA fitness when IF-side tag/valid/counter arrays, target muxing, and predicted-PC metadata lengthen the next-PC path more than CoreMark benefits from avoiding loop redirect bubbles.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (improvement, +1.93%): Dropping reset clears from the integer register file can improve FPGA fitness because pipeline-valid reset and x0 read forcing preserve architectural behavior while avoiding reset fanout and per-register muxing in an always-active datapath block.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r5s1 (regression, -6.89%): A one-entry ordered store buffer can lose CoreMark fitness when store-order interlocks, MMIO/trap classification, and dmem muxing add more MEM/control-path cost than random store-stall overlap recovers.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -61.05%): Even a single-entry loop predictor can badly regress when predicted-PC metadata, IF PC/tag compare muxing, and EX mismatch redirect logic lengthen critical control paths more than repeated CoreMark loop-branch bubble removal helps.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (regression, -2.40%): Pruning unused EX/MEM branch_taken/branch_target metadata did not improve FPGA fitness, suggesting these dead-looking pipeline fields were not on the binding path or were already optimized well enough that layout perturbation outweighed the small flop reduction.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (regression, -88.09%): Splitting EX with an EX1 operand register can destroy CoreMark fitness when it delays branch/JALR redirects and forces broad dependent-ALU interlocks, so operand-cone retiming must preserve bypass/redirect latency to pay off.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (regression, -48.05%): A JAL-only single-entry target predictor still regressed without fetch-side immediate decode because the IF PC compare/target mux, predicted-PC pipeline fields, and EX mismatch redirect logic outweighed CoreMark's repeated unconditional-jump bubble savings.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (regression, -53.28%): Replacing cold RV32M DIV/REM combinational operators with an iterative divider can severely regress CoreMark when the busy/start handshake, divider state, and 32-cycle latency perturb the hot pipeline more than removing the rarely used divide cone helps Fmax.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (broken, n/a): Registering dmem backpressure needs a real ready/valid or skid boundary at MEM; a lone pending/wait bit can hide the first stalled cycle from upstream control and let younger CoreMark memory-state updates be dropped or reordered.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r8s0 (improvement, +2.79%): Sharing one sign/zero-extended M-unit multiplier across MULH signedness variants can improve FPGA fitness because CoreMark rarely needs M throughput and parallel 64-bit products add DSP/LUT routing pressure.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778695238050,"end":1778695238058}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_098f252b08c14eb4016a04bc45e114819abe9fdd43e68ca76d"}},"id":"prt_e227f718400166InL7CSGSHZ3C","sessionID":"ses_1dd80c37dffeA0edlSklrIPTbJ","messageID":"msg_e227f3cc5001SNL03vP88B8YIj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778695238096,"sessionID":"ses_1dd80c37dffeA0edlSklrIPTbJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_xekRKUFzxf2KWcgGf6hCwddA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"micro_opt|hyp-20260513-001-r8s0|forward|reset|ALU|hazard|m_unit|reg_file|critical|Fmax","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 24 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-5327bba\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-13T13:08:01.185076Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Multicycle RV32M arithmetic unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU computes every multiply and divide result combinationally in\\nthe EX stage, including signed and unsigned 64-bit products plus divider and\\nremainder operators. That wide arithmetic cone is a likely Fmax limiter on\\nTang Nano 20K, while CoreMark's hot path should not need single-cycle DIV/REM\\nthroughput. Trading rare M-extension latency for a shorter common EX critical\\npath should improve iterations/second through higher clock frequency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU computes every multiply and divide result combinationally in\\nthe EX stage, including signed and unsigned 64-bit products plus divider and\\nremainder operators. That wide arithmetic cone is a likely Fmax limiter on\\nTang Nano 20K, while CoreMark's hot path should not need single-cycle DIV/REM\\nthroughput. Trading rare M-extension latency for a shorter common EX critical\\npath should improve iterations/second through higher clock frequency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M operations out of the always-combinational ALU path behind a\\nsmall multicycle M-unit handshake in EX. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/branch/address\\noperations purely combinational, but when the decoded alu_op is MUL/DIV/REM,\\nhold ID/EX and EX/MEM until the iterative arithmetic result is ready, then\\nretire normally through the existing MEM/WB and RVFI path. This should remove\\ndivider and large multiplier logic from the ordinary EX-stage timing path;\\nthe added stalls only affect uncommon M instructions and should be outweighed\\nby improved Fmax on the FPGA fitness metric.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Restrict the combinational ALU to fast RV32I operations and expose only lightweight M-op selection or helper logic needed by the new M-unit.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a multicycl...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve control flow in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark spends a significant fraction of its bracketed runtime in tight loops and conditional control flow. The current five-stage pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX, then flushes both IF and ID, so every taken branch or jump pays roughly a two-cycle redirect penalty. Reducing that penalty improves iterations/cycle without increasing retirement width or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark spends a significant fraction of its bracketed runtime in tight loops and conditional control flow. The current five-stage pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX, then flushes both IF and ID, so every taken branch or jump pays roughly a two-cycle redirect penalty. Reducing that penalty improves iterations/cycle without increasing retirement width or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move branch and JAL/JALR target/condition resolution from EX into the decode stage, with decode-stage operand forwarding from EX/MEM and MEM/WB for branch compares and JALR base operands. Keep the existing EX-stage trap/metadata path as the retirement source, but let ID drive redirect one cycle earlier when operands are available; stall only for unresolved load-to-branch/JALR dependencies. This should cut the common taken-control penalty from two bubbles to one while preserving RVFI order, trap reporting, and single-channel retirement.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ID-stage early redirect signals into the IF and hazard path while preserving the existing NRET=1 RVFI port set.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add early branch/JAL/JALR resolution using decoded control, immediates, regfile operands, and forwarded compare/base operands.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend forwarding ...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFNT branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an IF-stage static backward-taken/forward-not-taken predictor using the fetched instruction bits to compute B-type targets for negative branch immediates, and optionally early-predict JAL targets because they are unconditional PC-relative redirects. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction; mispredicted forward-taken branches, not-taken backward branches, and JALR still recover through the existing flush path. This should remove most loop-closing branch bubbles while preserving the single-retire RVFI contract because retirement remains unchanged at MEM/WB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles with the predicted next PC needed for EX-stage mispredict detection.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement static BTFNT next-PC selection for backward conditional branches and early PC-relative JAL prediction from fetched instruction bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Lat...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Simplify MEM load lane muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte-lane handling as explicit case muxes keyed by addr[1:0] instead of expressions like dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0] * 8) and mask << addr[1:0]. Keep the same misalignment trap behavior, RVFI aligned mem_addr reporting, replicated store data convention, and MEM/WB retirement boundary. This should reduce LUT depth and routing on the common load-data path while preserving the existing five-stage control flow and single-retire NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load-data shifts and shifted byte masks with explicit addr[1:0] case muxes for LB/LBU/LH/LHU/LW and store masks.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a one- or two-entry instruction skid buffer between IF and ID. The PC/imem side should continue fetching sequential instructions whenever the buffer has space, while the ID side consumes one buffered instruction only when ID/EX is ready. On redirect, flush the buffer and restart fetch at the EX-resolved target; on imem stalls, hold the outstanding fetch instead of emitting a synthetic NOP into decode. This should overlap random iStall cycles with existing back-end stalls and reduce front-end bubbles while preserving single-retire RVFI ordering and the existing EX-stage control-flow correctness.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"descr...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny return-address stack predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small 4-entry return-address stack that predicts only canonical returns\\n(JALR x0, 0(x1/x5)) in IF. Push pc+4 for link-register calls when they resolve,\\npop/predict the stack top for returns, and carry the predicted next PC through the\\npipeline so EX redirects only on mismatch. This keeps ordinary branch fetch as pc+4,\\navoids B-type immediate decode and target adders in the IF critical path, and should\\nrecover part of the call/return control-flow penalty with modest LUT/FF cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC and return-predicted metadata to IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM bundles for mispredict detection and RAS bookkeeping.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect canonical return encodings in the fetched instruction and select the RAS top as the next PC only when the stack is nonempty....\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against the\\nraw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction, regardless of whether\\nthat instruction actually consumes those operands. For I-type immediates,\\nloads, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK, some of those fields are\\nimmediates or destination bits rather than true sources. Any accidental match\\nwith the preceding load rd inserts an unnecessary bubble, directly reducing\\nCoreMark iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against the\\nraw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction, regardless of whether\\nthat instruction actually consumes those operands. For I-type immediates,\\nloads, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK, some of those fields are\\nimmediates or destination bits rather than true sources. Any accidental match\\nwith the preceding load rd inserts an unnecessary bubble, directly reducing\\nCoreMark iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Make the load-use interlock source-aware by qualifying the rd comparisons with\\nsimple decoded uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 signals for the instruction currently in\\nIF/ID. Keep the existing one-cycle stall for real load consumers, but avoid\\nstalling on unused source fields such as OP-IMM rs2 bits, U/J-type operand\\nfields, and SYSTEM/FENCE encodings. This should improve CPI under CoreMark's\\nload-heavy code while adding only small opcode decode logic off the main ALU\\nand memory datapaths, so Fmax should be largely preserved.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive or wire IF/ID source-use qualifiers into the hazard unit without changing the NRET=1 top-level RVFI interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Load-use MEM bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The previous structural attempts spent LUTs and timing on front-end control-flow machinery, and the log shows those changes either broke correctness or regressed fitness. The current five-stage core still has the classic one-cycle load-use interlock even though the benchmark memory is zero-wait in FPGA and only randomly stalled in cosim. CoreMark has frequent dependent loads through pointer-heavy list, matrix, and state code, so removing this bubble can improve iterations per cycle without adding predictor target adders to the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The previous structural attempts spent LUTs and timing on front-end control-flow machinery, and the log shows those changes either broke correctness or regressed fitness. The current five-stage core still has the classic one-cycle load-use interlock even though the benchmark memory is zero-wait in FPGA and only randomly stalled in cosim. CoreMark has frequent dependent loads through pointer-heavy list, matrix, and state code, so removing this bubble can improve iterations per cycle without adding predictor target adders to the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a MEM-to-EX load-data bypass path that lets an instruction immediately behind a load proceed into EX when the load is in MEM and dmem is ready. Compute the existing load extraction result combinationally in MEM, expose it to the forwarding network, and add a forwarding select for EX operands that chooses the current MEM load result over the older EX/MEM ALU address. Keep the load-use stall only when the load will not have valid data that cycle, such as a dmem stall or a misaligned/trapping load. This structural bypass should remove many single-cycle bubbles while preserving the NRET=1 retirement boundary and RVFI order at MEM/WB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\"...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Decode-stage JAL predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The prior predictor attempts regressed because they placed branch target decode,\\ntarget adders, return detection, and prediction muxes directly on the IF PC path.\\nCoreMark still pays the existing EX redirect penalty for every unconditional JAL,\\nand JAL targets are PC-relative with no register dependency or branch condition.\\nPredicting only JAL in decode should recover one control-flow bubble for calls and\\nlong jumps while avoiding the risky fetch-path predictor logic that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The prior predictor attempts regressed because they placed branch target decode,\\ntarget adders, return detection, and prediction muxes directly on the IF PC path.\\nCoreMark still pays the existing EX redirect penalty for every unconditional JAL,\\nand JAL targets are PC-relative with no register dependency or branch condition.\\nPredicting only JAL in decode should recover one control-flow bubble for calls and\\nlong jumps while avoiding the risky fetch-path predictor logic that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a narrow decode-stage always-taken predictor for legal JAL instructions only.\\nID computes pc+imm for JAL, redirects fetch one cycle before EX would, and records\\nthe predicted next PC in the ID/EX bundle. EX then suppresses the normal JAL redirect\\nwhen the resolved jump target matches the predicted target, but retains the existing\\nEX recovery path for conditional branches, JALR, illegal instructions, and any target\\nmismatch. Because the predictor excludes branches and returns, it needs no B-type\\nimmediate decode in IF, no RAS state, and no operand forwarding, making it a smaller\\npredictor angle with a better chance of improving CoreMark iterations/cycle without\\nsacrificing the current high Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add p...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Source-qualified load interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\\nsource bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\\narchitecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\\ninstructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\\niterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\\nsource bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\\narchitecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\\ninstructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\\niterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny source-use decode for the IF/ID instruction and qualify the existing\\nload-use interlock with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. This is a narrower retry of the\\nearlier source-aware load-use idea: do not mask or reinterpret RVFI operand\\nreporting, and do not add MEM bypass selects or fetch prediction paths. The\\ncore should keep the one-cycle stall for true load consumers while avoiding\\nfalse stalls on OP-IMM rs2 fields, U/J-type immediates, FENCE, SYSTEM/EBREAK,\\nand other instructions that do not read both source registers.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive simple IF/ID uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 qualifiers from opcode/funct class and pass them only to the hazard unit.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate load-use rd comparisons with the source-use qualifiers while preserving existing dmem, imem, redirect, and M-unit stall priority.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive simple IF/ID use...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register IF/ID fetch boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end feeds imem_data directly through decode, immediate\\ngeneration, regfile address decode, hazard checks, and into the ID/EX\\nregister in a single cycle. Prior structural attempts tried to hide stalls or\\nreduce bubbles with added prediction and bypass control, but those changes\\nregressed by lengthening already sensitive mux/control paths. A real IF/ID\\nregister is a simpler structural retiming that targets Fmax directly.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end feeds imem_data directly through decode, immediate\\ngeneration, regfile address decode, hazard checks, and into the ID/EX\\nregister in a single cycle. Prior structural attempts tried to hide stalls or\\nreduce bubbles with added prediction and bypass control, but those changes\\nregressed by lengthening already sensitive mux/control paths. A real IF/ID\\nregister is a simpler structural retiming that targets Fmax directly.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a proper IF/ID pipeline register inside the fetch stage, so fetched\\ninstruction, PC, and valid are captured before decode sees them. The PC still\\nadvances only when the downstream ID stage can accept the entry, and redirect\\nflushes the registered IF/ID payload before wrong-path state can retire. This\\nadds one front-end cycle and may slightly increase taken-control penalty, but\\nit removes the imem-to-decoder combinational path and should improve FPGA\\nFmax enough to raise CoreMark iter/sec without changing the NRET=1 retirement\\ncontract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep the existing IF/ID bundle shape, but document and use it as a registered pipeline boundary rather than a combinational fetch payload.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an IF/ID register for pc, instruction, and valid; hold it on deco...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny resolved-target BTB\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves all taken branches and jumps in EX, so tight CoreMark loops pay a two-bubble redirect penalty. Prior predictor attempts regressed because they decoded immediates, computed targets, or managed return-stack state on the front-end critical path. A small BTB trained from already-resolved EX redirects can target the same loop bubbles while avoiding fetch-stage target arithmetic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves all taken branches and jumps in EX, so tight CoreMark loops pay a two-bubble redirect penalty. Prior predictor attempts regressed because they decoded immediates, computed targets, or managed return-stack state on the front-end critical path. A small BTB trained from already-resolved EX redirects can target the same loop bubbles while avoiding fetch-stage target arithmetic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped branch target buffer that stores resolved taken conditional-branch targets, preferably only backward loop branches, along with a compact PC tag and a 2-bit confidence counter. IF predicts to the stored target on a tag hit with a taken counter, otherwise it keeps the existing pc+4 path; EX updates the BTB after branch resolution and flushes on any predicted/resolved next-PC mismatch. Because the target is stored from the prior execution, the fetch path adds only a small tag compare and next-PC mux instead of B/J immediate decode and target adders, which should recover loop-closing branch bubbles with less Fmax damage than the previous predictor attempts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Carry predicted next-PC metadata through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX can distinguish correct BTB predictions from mispredictions without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Imple...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Drop regfile reset fanout\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a for-loop,\\nwhich forces reset muxing or reset routing onto the whole small RF array. After\\nthe M-unit split, remaining FPGA Fmax is likely limited by ordinary datapath\\nand control fanout rather than rare arithmetic. CoreMark initializes the state\\nit uses, x0 is already hardwired on reads, and RVFI correctness depends on\\nretired architectural behavior rather than power-on values of unused registers.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a for-loop,\\nwhich forces reset muxing or reset routing onto the whole small RF array. After\\nthe M-unit split, remaining FPGA Fmax is likely limited by ordinary datapath\\nand control fanout rather than rare arithmetic. CoreMark initializes the state\\nit uses, x0 is already hardwired on reads, and RVFI correctness depends on\\nretired architectural behavior rather than power-on values of unused registers.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the explicit reset clear from the integer register file and keep only\\nthe synchronous write path for nonzero destination registers. Reads of x0 stay\\nforced to zero, same-cycle write-first bypass stays unchanged, and reset of the\\npipeline control/valid bits still prevents spurious retirement after reset.\\nThis should reduce reset fanout and per-register muxing in a timing-sensitive,\\nalways-active block without changing CPI, branch behavior, memory behavior, or\\nthe NRET=1 RVFI interface. The change is deliberately narrower than prior\\nfailed micro-opts: it does not touch hazard detection, RVFI operand reporting,\\nMEM load extraction, or any front-end prediction path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the reset-time loop that clears all 32 registers while preser...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Ordered one-entry store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts spent timing and LUTs on the front end or on load\\nbypass paths, and those changes either regressed fitness or broke stall\\nhandling. The current core still freezes the entire pipeline whenever a store\\nreaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, even though independent ALU, branch, and\\nregister-only instructions behind that store could execute while the store is\\nwaiting. CoreMark has frequent data stores and the apples-to-apples cosim\\ninjects random dmem stalls, so store backpressure is a promising structural\\ntarget that avoids fetch-path target adders and load-result critical muxes.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts spent timing and LUTs on the front end or on load\\nbypass paths, and those changes either regressed fitness or broke stall\\nhandling. The current core still freezes the entire pipeline whenever a store\\nreaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, even though independent ALU, branch, and\\nregister-only instructions behind that store could execute while the store is\\nwaiting. CoreMark has frequent data stores and the apples-to-apples cosim\\ninjects random dmem stalls, so store backpressure is a promising structural\\ntarget that avoids fetch-path target adders and load-result critical muxes.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry ordered store buffer at the MEM boundary. A regular data\\nstore can retire into the buffer with its address, byte mask, write data, and\\nRVFI metadata captured, allowing the front of the pipeline to keep executing\\nnon-memory instructions while the buffer drives dmem until dmem_ready accepts\\nthe write. Preserve precise in-order behavior by stalling any younger load,\\nstore, MMIO access, FENCE, EBREAK, or illegal/trapping instruction until the\\nbuffer drains; MMIO marker/UART stores should bypass the buffer and keep the\\nexisting blocking behavior so CoreMark timing brackets re...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Single-entry loop target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core fetches sequentially and pays the existing EX-stage redirect\\npenalty on every taken loop-closing branch. Earlier predictor attempts\\nregressed because they placed immediate decode, target adders, BTB arrays,\\ncounters, or RAS control on the fetch path. A predictor for this slot should\\ntherefore be much narrower: reuse targets already resolved in EX and add the\\nsmallest possible fetch-side structure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core fetches sequentially and pays the existing EX-stage redirect\\npenalty on every taken loop-closing branch. Earlier predictor attempts\\nregressed because they placed immediate decode, target adders, BTB arrays,\\ncounters, or RAS control on the fetch path. A predictor for this slot should\\ntherefore be much narrower: reuse targets already resolved in EX and add the\\nsmallest possible fetch-side structure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry resolved-loop target predictor trained only by taken\\nbackward conditional branches. The entry stores one branch PC and its resolved\\ntarget; IF predicts taken only when the current PC equals that stored PC,\\notherwise it keeps the existing pc+4 behavior. Carry predicted-taken and\\npredicted-next-PC metadata to EX so the normal redirect path fires only on a\\nmismatch, and invalidate the entry when that same branch resolves not-taken\\nat loop exit. This should recover repeated inner-loop branch bubbles in\\nCoreMark while avoiding the fetch target adders, multi-entry tag arrays,\\nconfidence counters, and return-stack machinery that hurt prior predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add minimal predicted-taken and predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles for EX-stage mismatch detection.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement ...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Prune dead EX/MEM branch metadata\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already won most of its fitness from removing broad\\ntiming/fanout costs, while recent attempts that add prediction, buffering,\\nbypassing, or memory-ordering control have regressed. The EX/MEM bundle still\\ncarries branch_taken and branch_target fields that are assigned every cycle\\nbut are not consumed by MEM, WB, RVFI, hazard, or forwarding logic. Those 33\\ndead flops and their input adders/mux routes sit in an always-active pipeline\\nboundary, so pruning them is a low-risk micro-optimization for LUT/FF count\\nand routing delay without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already won most of its fitness from removing broad\\ntiming/fanout costs, while recent attempts that add prediction, buffering,\\nbypassing, or memory-ordering control have regressed. The EX/MEM bundle still\\ncarries branch_taken and branch_target fields that are assigned every cycle\\nbut are not consumed by MEM, WB, RVFI, hazard, or forwarding logic. Those 33\\ndead flops and their input adders/mux routes sit in an always-active pipeline\\nboundary, so pruning them is a low-risk micro-optimization for LUT/FF count\\nand routing delay without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t and stop\\nregistering them in ex_stage. Keep redirect and pc_next computation exactly as\\nthey are today, because pc_next is the RVFI-visible resolved next PC and the\\nredirect output is still the only live control-flow signal. This should trim\\ndead sequential state and reduce EX-stage fanout/routing pressure while\\npreserving the NRET=1 RVFI contract, trap behavior, memory behavior, and all\\nexisting stall/flush priorities.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove unused branch_taken and...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Pipeline EX operand retiming\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added fetch prediction, skid buffering, load bypassing,\\nor store buffering all paid too much control-path cost. The current core's remaining\\nhigh-fanout structural path is more basic: ID/EX values pass through forwarding muxes,\\nALU operand selection, ALU or branch compare/target logic, and into EX/MEM plus the\\nredirect path in one cycle. Retiming that boundary can target Fmax without adding a\\npredictor, memory ordering structure, or RVFI contract change.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added fetch prediction, skid buffering, load bypassing,\\nor store buffering all paid too much control-path cost. The current core's remaining\\nhigh-fanout structural path is more basic: ID/EX values pass through forwarding muxes,\\nALU operand selection, ALU or branch compare/target logic, and into EX/MEM plus the\\nredirect path in one cycle. Retiming that boundary can target Fmax without adding a\\npredictor, memory ordering structure, or RVFI contract change.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the existing EX stage into a lightweight EX1 operand/metadata register and an EX2\\nexecute/redirect stage. EX1 captures the forwarded rs1/rs2 values, selected ALU operands,\\ndecoded control, immediate, PC, and RVFI source data; EX2 performs the ALU operation,\\nbranch/jump resolution, M-unit handshake, and drives the existing EX/MEM payload. Add the\\nminimal hazard/forwarding adjustments needed for the extra execute stage, preferring a\\none-cycle interlock on immediately dependent ALU consumers over wide new bypass muxes if\\nthat keeps timing short. This structural retiming should shorten the common forwarding-to-\\nALU-to-EX/MEM cone and may raise Tang Nano 20K Fmax enough to offset a small CPI cost,\\nwhile preserving NRET=1 retirement at MEM/WB and all RVFI ordering/trap behavior.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\"...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative M divider\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The largest proven fitness gain for this core came from moving RV32M arithmetic\\nout of the ordinary EX ALU path, but the current m_unit still contains wide\\ncombinational DIV/REM operators behind a one-cycle result register. Even if\\nthose operations are rare in CoreMark, the FPGA still has to place and time\\nthe divider/remainder cone, so it can cap Fmax or perturb routing for the hot\\nRV32I pipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The largest proven fitness gain for this core came from moving RV32M arithmetic\\nout of the ordinary EX ALU path, but the current m_unit still contains wide\\ncombinational DIV/REM operators behind a one-cycle result register. Even if\\nthose operations are rare in CoreMark, the FPGA still has to place and time\\nthe divider/remainder cone, so it can cap Fmax or perturb routing for the hot\\nRV32I pipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the one-cycle DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU implementation in m_unit with a small\\niterative restoring divider that runs only after a divide or remainder starts.\\nKeep MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU on the existing short registered path so any\\nmultiply use does not pay a 32-cycle penalty, and keep the existing EX-stage\\nhold/valid handshake as the only pipeline interface. This should remove the\\nexpensive combinational divider/remainder logic from the FPGA timing closure\\nproblem while adding CPI only for uncommon divide/remainder instructions.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/m_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with an iterative signed/unsigned divider state machine while preserving ALTOPS behavior under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Adjust the existing M-unit busy/valid handshake only as needed so EX holds until multi-cycle DIV/REM completion and still clears completed results exactly once.\"}]}, \"expec...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Register dmem stall boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts added front-end prediction, fetch buffering, load\\nbypassing, store buffering, or a deeper EX pipe, and each paid too much in\\nmux/control cost or correctness complexity. A smaller structural target is\\nthe current dmem stall path: io_dmemReady fans combinationally through the\\nhazard unit into PC hold, ID hold, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB valid clearing in\\nthe same cycle. CoreMark's apples-to-apples mode injects random dmem stalls,\\nso this control path is active during evaluation, and reducing its fanout may\\nimprove Fmax without changing the visible memory ordering contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts added front-end prediction, fetch buffering, load\\nbypassing, store buffering, or a deeper EX pipe, and each paid too much in\\nmux/control cost or correctness complexity. A smaller structural target is\\nthe current dmem stall path: io_dmemReady fans combinationally through the\\nhazard unit into PC hold, ID hold, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB valid clearing in\\nthe same cycle. CoreMark's apples-to-apples mode injects random dmem stalls,\\nso this control path is active during evaluation, and reducing its fanout may\\nimprove Fmax without changing the visible memory ordering contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-cycle registered MEM busy/accepted boundary for data-memory\\noperations. When a load or store enters MEM, capture whether it is waiting for\\ndmem_ready in a small state bit local to the MEM/hazard interface; while that\\nbit is set, hold EX/MEM and clear MEM/WB valid exactly as today, but drive the\\nglobal pipeline stalls from the registered busy state rather than directly\\nfrom io_dmemReady. Keep dmem_addr, dmem_wdata, dmem_wen, dmem_ren, RVFI memory\\nmasks/data, misalignment traps, and all in-order retirement behavior\\nunchanged. This deliberately accepts at most one extra cycle on the first\\nstal...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Decode-only JAL redirect predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core regressed because they added target\\nadders, tag compares, return-stack state, or predicted-PC muxing directly to\\nthe IF next-PC path. The current core still pays the EX redirect penalty for\\nevery unconditional JAL, and JAL needs no operand forwarding or direction\\nprediction once its instruction reaches decode.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core regressed because they added target\\nadders, tag compares, return-stack state, or predicted-PC muxing directly to\\nthe IF next-PC path. The current core still pays the EX redirect penalty for\\nevery unconditional JAL, and JAL needs no operand forwarding or direction\\nprediction once its instruction reaches decode.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a decode-stage predictor for legal JAL instructions only. ID already has\\nthe instruction, PC, and immediate generator output, so it can compute the JAL\\ntarget and redirect fetch one cycle earlier than EX without adding any logic\\nto the IF PC increment path. Carry a small predicted-next-PC flag/value into\\nID/EX so EX suppresses its normal JAL redirect when the ID prediction matches,\\nwhile all conditional branches, JALR, illegal instructions, and mismatches use\\nthe existing EX recovery path. This avoids the failed fetch-side predictor\\nstructures while recovering one bubble on CoreMark calls and PC-relative jumps.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add minimal predicted-valid and predicted-next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles for decode-stage JAL prediction validation.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect legal JAL in decode, compute pc plus J-immediate, emit an early redirect, and latch the prediction metadata into ID/EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the ID...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Share M-unit multiplier hardware\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already removed RV32M arithmetic from the ordinary EX\\nALU path, but m_unit still builds three separate 64-bit multiplier products\\nin parallel for MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU signedness variants. CoreMark uses\\nM operations rarely enough that throughput beyond the existing one-cycle\\nregistered M-unit is not the main limiter, while the extra DSP/LUT/routing\\npressure can still depress FPGA Fmax or perturb placement of the hot RV32I\\npipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already removed RV32M arithmetic from the ordinary EX\\nALU path, but m_unit still builds three separate 64-bit multiplier products\\nin parallel for MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU signedness variants. CoreMark uses\\nM operations rarely enough that throughput beyond the existing one-cycle\\nregistered M-unit is not the main limiter, while the extra DSP/LUT/routing\\npressure can still depress FPGA Fmax or perturb placement of the hot RV32I\\npipeline.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the parallel signed-signed, unsigned-unsigned, and signed-unsigned\\nproduct generation in m_unit with one shared signed multiplier fed by\\nsign/zero-extended operands selected from the M opcode. MUL can take the low\\nhalf of the same product because low 32 bits are independent of operand\\nsignedness; MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU select the high half with the appropriate\\noperand extension. Keep the existing start/valid/clear handshake, one-cycle\\nM latency, DIV/REM behavior, and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions unchanged.\\nThis should trim multiplier area and routing without adding CPI, front-end\\nprediction logic, memory ordering state, or any RVFI-visible behavior change.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/m_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Use a single sign-controlled widened multiplier for MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU while pres...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Register WB result at MEM boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The recent structural attempts mostly lost fitness by adding control-flow\\nprediction, buffering, memory overlap, or deeper execute-stage interlocks.\\nA safer structural target is the existing MEM/WB-to-WB combinational path:\\nthe selected writeback value is still muxed after the MEM/WB register, then\\nfans out to the regfile write port, same-cycle regfile bypass, EX forwarding,\\nand RVFI rd_wdata. Registering that selected value at the retirement boundary\\nshould shorten a hot fanout path without changing CPI, branch timing, memory\\nordering, or the NRET=1 external contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The recent structural attempts mostly lost fitness by adding control-flow\\nprediction, buffering, memory overlap, or deeper execute-stage interlocks.\\nA safer structural target is the existing MEM/WB-to-WB combinational path:\\nthe selected writeback value is still muxed after the MEM/WB register, then\\nfans out to the regfile write port, same-cycle regfile bypass, EX forwarding,\\nand RVFI rd_wdata. Registering that selected value at the retirement boundary\\nshould shorten a hot fanout path without changing CPI, branch timing, memory\\nordering, or the NRET=1 external contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a preselected rd_wdata/writeback-result field to the MEM/WB pipeline\\nbundle and compute it inside mem_stage before the MEM/WB register captures.\\nFor loads this field captures the sign/zero-extended load result; for ALU,\\nJAL, JALR, AUIPC, LUI, and M-extension operations it captures the existing\\nEX/MEM alu_result. Then simplify wb_stage into a pass-through of the\\nregistered writeback value instead of a post-register mem_to_reg mux. This\\nstructural retiming preserves the same retirement boundary and RVFI data, but\\nremoves the load-vs-ALU mux from the next cycle's forwarding/regfile/RVFI\\nfanout cone, which may improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax with ess...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Decode-stage backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost fitness when they added BTB, RAS, tag compare,\\ncounter, or target-adder logic to the IF next-PC path. The current core still\\npays a two-bubble EX redirect penalty on taken loop-closing branches, which\\nare the predictor opportunity most likely to matter for CoreMark. A predictor\\nthat waits until decode can use the already-fetched instruction and decoded\\nbranch control while keeping fetch as the current simple pc+4 path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost fitness when they added BTB, RAS, tag compare,\\ncounter, or target-adder logic to the IF next-PC path. The current core still\\npays a two-bubble EX redirect penalty on taken loop-closing branches, which\\nare the predictor opportunity most likely to matter for CoreMark. A predictor\\nthat waits until decode can use the already-fetched instruction and decoded\\nbranch control while keeping fetch as the current simple pc+4 path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a static decode-stage predictor for legal backward conditional branches\\nonly. ID uses the existing immediate generator and decoded is_branch signal to\\nrecognize negative B-type offsets, computes pc+imm, and redirects fetch one\\ncycle earlier than EX would. Carry predicted-valid and predicted-next-PC into\\nID/EX so EX suppresses the normal redirect when the branch is actually taken\\nto the predicted target, or redirects to pc+4 on the loop-exit not-taken\\nmisprediction. Forward branches, JAL, JALR, illegal encodings, and all memory\\nor RVFI behavior stay on the existing path. This targets loop bubbles without\\nreintroducing the failed IF-side predictor structures.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add minimal predicted-valid and predicted-next-PC fields to the ID/EX bundle for EX-stage branch predict...","metadata":{"matches":24,"truncated":false},"title":"micro_opt|hyp-20260513-001-r8s0|forward|reset|ALU|hazard|m_unit|reg_file|critical|Fmax","time":{"start":1778695238085,"end":1778695238095}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_098f252b08c14eb4016a04bc45e124819a92fce211c549627b"}},"id":"prt_e227f71a40010Ozz6OWqFGEgrw","sessionID":"ses_1dd80c37dffeA0edlSklrIPTbJ","messageID":"msg_e227f3cc5001SNL03vP88B8YIj"}}
