{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778695301851,"sessionID":"ses_1dd80c37dffeA0edlSklrIPTbJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_vt2tFVJacGlkWWnIaCrCnGZ7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\n+title: \"Narrow MEM/WB control state\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent micro-optimization wins came from removing always-present FPGA timing\n+  and routing pressure, while attempts that added prediction, bypassing, or\n+  stall-hiding control usually regressed. The current MEM/WB register still\n+  carries the full decode control bundle even though the writeback and RVFI\n+  retirement logic only consume a few bits after the MEM stage. Pruning that\n+  cold control state should reduce flop count, muxing, and routing without\n+  changing CoreMark CPI or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the full ctrl_t field in mem_wb_t with a narrow retirement/writeback\n+  control subset containing only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Keep\n+  the existing full ctrl_t through ID/EX and EX/MEM, because the execute and\n+  memory stages still need branch, memory width, sign-extension, and M-op\n+  controls. In mem_stage, collapse ctrl_with_trap into the narrow MEM/WB\n+  fields after misalignment handling, and update wb_stage and core RVFI trap\n+  references to use the narrow fields. This should trim unused MEM/WB control\n+  flops and fanout while preserving all memory masks/data, load results,\n+  writeback behavior, RVFI order, and trap reporting.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Introduce a narrow MEM/WB control type and replace mem_wb_t.ctrl with only the retirement/writeback bits used after MEM.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Populate the narrow MEM/WB control fields after misalignment trap handling instead of carrying the full ctrl_t bundle forward.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Read reg_write and mem_to_reg from the narrowed MEM/WB control subset with identical writeback behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Read the RVFI trap bit from the narrowed MEM/WB control subset while preserving the NRET=1 port contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,33 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\n+title: \"Narrow MEM/WB control state\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent micro-optimization wins came from removing always-present FPGA timing\n+  and routing pressure, while attempts that added prediction, bypassing, or\n+  stall-hiding control usually regressed. The current MEM/WB register still\n+  carries the full decode control bundle even though the writeback and RVFI\n+  retirement logic only consume a few bits after the MEM stage. Pruning that\n+  cold control state should reduce flop count, muxing, and routing without\n+  changing CoreMark CPI or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the full ctrl_t field in mem_wb_t with a narrow retirement/writeback\n+  control subset containing only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Keep\n+  the existing full ctrl_t through ID/EX and EX/MEM, because the execute and\n+  memory