{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778696192705,"sessionID":"ses_1dd72e6daffec3mB05znqTDbW4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_TRNi2V53Otu056O349NZrAxD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n2: title: Split MEM RVFI sideband path\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The latest successful structural change split RVFI-only metadata away from the hot execution payloads and improved fitness without changing CPI. The remaining MEM stage still computes and registers RVFI memory sideband fields in the same combinational block and pipeline boundary that drives dmem, load extraction, writeback, and forwarding. A narrower structural separation in MEM is a safer follow-on than adding predictors, store buffers, load bypasses, or deeper execute retiming, all of which have regressed or broken previously.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Split the MEM-stage memory sideband work into a parallel RVFI-only path while keeping the execution path limited to dmem request signals, load_data, rd, compact control, and valid. The hot MEM/WB execution register should no longer share bundle assignment, hold, and mux fanout with RVFI-only mem_addr, mem_rmask, mem_wmask, mem_rdata, mem_wdata, pc, source values, and instruction fields. Preserve the existing single-retire MEM/WB retirement point, dmem stall behavior, misalignment traps, RVFI aligned-memory reporting, and NRET=1 port shape. This should reduce routing and enable fanout around the MEM boundary with little CPI risk, extending the proven RVFI-shadow split into the last stage where sideband metadata still sits next to timing-sensitive load/writeback logic.\n8: expected_impact:\n9:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n10:   confidence: medium\n11: changes:\n12:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n13:     description: \"Refine the MEM/WB execution and RVFI shadow payloads so memory sideband fields are structurally isolated from the hot writeback/forwarding state.\"\n14:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n15:     description: \"Separate MEM execution capture from RVFI memory sideband capture while preserving dmem outputs, load extraction, misalignment traps, hold_wb behavior, and RVFI aligned-memory fields.\"\n16:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n17:     description: \"Keep top-level RVFI wiring unchanged while adapting to the more isolated MEM/WB execution and RVFI shadow paths.\"\n\n(End of file - total 17 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\ntitle: Split MEM RVFI sideband path\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The latest successful structural change split RVFI-only metadata away from the hot execution payloads and improved fitness without changing CPI. The remaining MEM stage still computes and registers RVFI memory sideband fields in the same combinational block and pipeline boundary that drives dmem, load extraction, writeback, and forwarding. A narrower structural separation in MEM is a safer follow-on than adding predictors, store buffers, load bypasses, or deeper execute retiming, all of which have regressed or broken previously.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split the MEM-stage memory sideband work into a parallel RVFI-only path while keeping the execution path limited to dmem request signals, load_data, rd, compact control, and valid. The hot MEM/WB execution register should no longer share bundle assignment, hold, and mux fanout with RVFI-only mem_addr, mem_rmask, mem_wmask, mem_rdata, mem_wdata, pc, source values, and instruction fields. Preserve the existing single-retire MEM/WB retirement point, dmem stall behavior, misalignment traps, RVFI aligned-memory reporting, and NRET=1 port shape. This should reduce routing and enable fanout around the MEM boundary with little CPI risk, extending the proven RVFI-shadow split into the last stage where sideband metadata still sits next to timing-sensitive load/writeback logic.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Refine the MEM/WB execution and RVFI shadow payloads so memory sideband fields are structurally isolated from the hot writeback/forwarding state.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Separate MEM execution capture from RVFI memory sideband capture while preserving dmem outputs, load extraction, misalignment traps, hold_wb behavior, and RVFI aligned-memory fields.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Keep top-level RVFI wiring unchanged while adapting to the more isolated MEM/WB execution and RVFI shadow paths.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778696192700,"end":1778696192704}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d9e887081d25eb016a04bfff50d4819a8d6522ab17e0acb4"}},"id":"prt_e228dfdbe0015Z1sM5vc4VeZNg","sessionID":"ses_1dd72e6daffec3mB05znqTDbW4","messageID":"msg_e228de158001KRKPzg8vojPS5U"}}
