{"type":"text","timestamp":1778698745660,"sessionID":"ses_1dd4b95daffeUPuCkcS77kE0Dc","part":{"id":"prt_e22b4f54b0017KPr50xhbAEVIR","messageID":"msg_e22b49d46001TsrjVIg6OQ5zsn","sessionID":"ses_1dd4b95daffeUPuCkcS77kE0Dc","type":"text","text":"The relevant structural history shows most front-end buffering, prediction, memory bypass/buffering, and deeper EX retiming regressed or broke; the only durable structural win was reducing hot-path metadata/fanout. I’m writing a conservative structural hypothesis that targets a remaining always-active fanout structure rather than adding CPI-changing control machinery.","time":{"start":1778698745163,"end":1778698745659},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_00ab77b14caf5196016a04c9f90c50819b957103fd3c30ce8a","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778698765490,"sessionID":"ses_1dd4b95daffeUPuCkcS77kE0Dc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_CNe56YY838MrSqi54f2yLqDz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Localize WB-to-ID bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior structural attempts show that adding predictors, skid buffers, store buffers,\n+  load bypasses, or deeper execute retiming usually costs more FPGA fitness than it\n+  recovers. The remaining promising structural direction is to reduce always-active\n+  fanout and muxing without changing CPI or control-flow timing. The integer regfile\n+  currently embeds write-first same-cycle bypass compares and 32-bit muxes on both\n+  combinational read ports, so WB write-enable/address/data fan out through the\n+  register file as well as to forwarding, RVFI, and writeback.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Move the same-cycle WB-to-ID bypass out of reg_file and into id_stage as two local\n+  read-data selects after the raw register-file read. The reg_file would become a\n+  simpler 2-read/1-write array with x0 forcing only, while id_stage receives the WB\n+  write port and selects wb_w_data for rs1/rs2 when the decoded source matches the\n+  retiring destination. This preserves the existing architectural behavior needed\n+  for consumers that are too far from the writer to be covered by EX forwarding, but\n+  localizes the write-first muxing near decode and may let synthesis pack the regfile\n+  array and WB fanout better. It avoids changing pipeline depth, redirect timing,\n+  memory ordering, RVFI retirement, or the NRET=1 top-level contract.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove embedded same-cycle write-first bypass muxes from the combinational read ports, keeping x0 forcing and the synchronous write behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Accept the WB write-enable/address/data signals and apply local rs1/rs2 bypass selection before filling the ID/EX register.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the existing WB write port signals into id_stage while preserving the current NRET=1 RVFI port set and pipeline control.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,31 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Localize WB-to-ID bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior structural attempts show that adding predictors, skid buffers, store buffers,\n+  load bypasses, or deeper execute retiming usually costs more FPGA fitness than it\n+  recovers. The remaining promising structural direction is to reduce always-active\n+  fanout and muxing without changing CPI or control-flow timing. The integer regfile\n+  currently embeds write-first same-cycle bypass compares and 32-bit muxes on both\n+  combinational read ports, so WB write-enable/address/data fan out through the\n+  register file as well as to forwarding, RVFI, and writeback.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Move the same-cycle WB-to-ID bypass out of reg_file and into id_stage as two local\n+  read-data selects after the raw register-file read. The reg_file would become a\n+  simpler 2-read/1-write array with