{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778699870395,"sessionID":"ses_1dd3adec3ffemJytt3LES5g7wK","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_SDBbE4VFLRHsszDIIRGQyflq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Source-aware load interlock\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline still treats both raw rs bitfields of the\n+  instruction in IF/ID as real consumers when deciding whether a preceding load\n+  must insert a bubble. That is structurally conservative but overly broad:\n+  OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK either ignore rs2 or\n+  ignore both source fields, so accidental matches against the load rd can\n+  create false load-use stalls. CoreMark is load-heavy, and reducing bubbles\n+  without adding predictors, MEM bypass muxes, store buffers, or deeper EX\n+  staging is one of the few remaining CPI improvements with modest timing risk.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny source-use classifier for the IF/ID instruction and feed its\n+  uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 bits only into the load-use hazard comparison. Keep the\n+  existing one-cycle interlock for real consumers, but suppress the stall when\n+  the matching raw bitfield is actually an immediate, destination, or unused\n+  SYSTEM/FENCE field. This should improve iterations/cycle by removing false\n+  bubbles while leaving RVFI rs1/rs2 address and data reporting unchanged, which\n+  avoids the failure mode from earlier source-aware attempts. The added opcode\n+  decode is local to hazard control and should be cheaper than prior structural\n+  approaches that put adders, predictors, or new bypass selects on hot paths.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Derive IF/ID uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 qualifiers from the fetched instruction opcode/funct class and pass them only to hazard_unit.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Gate the existing load-use rd comparisons with source-use qualifiers while preserving current imem, dmem, redirect, and M-unit stall priority.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Source-aware load interlock\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline still treats both raw rs bitfields of the\n+  instruction in IF/ID as real consumers when deciding whether a preceding load\n+  must insert a bubble. That is structurally conservative but overly broad:\n+  OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK either ignore rs2 or\n+  ignore both source fields, so accidental matches against the load rd can\n+  create false load-use stalls. CoreMark is load-heavy, and reducing bubbles\n+  without adding predictors, MEM bypass muxes, store buffers, or deeper EX\n+  staging is one of the few remaining CPI improvements with modest timing risk.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny source-use classifier for the IF/ID instruction and feed its\n+  uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 bits only into the load-use hazard comparison. Keep the\n+  existing one-cycle interlock for real consumers, bu