{"type":"text","timestamp":1778678975322,"sessionID":"ses_1de7941beffepjxUFM8Diz3UWE","part":{"id":"prt_e218743d600102YSYHG6PAiVPw","messageID":"msg_e2187049e002fNivzFCod7zc3u","sessionID":"ses_1de7941beffepjxUFM8Diz3UWE","type":"text","text":"I’m writing the hypothesis as a one-entry/two-entry fetch buffer structural proposal: decouple PC/imem from ID so random instruction stalls and load-use/M-unit bubbles can overlap instead of injecting front-end bubbles directly into ID/EX.","time":{"start":1778678973398,"end":1778678975321},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_01592251a661ee99016a047cbd4be08198851394d197138e0a","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778678995899,"sessionID":"ses_1de7941beffepjxUFM8Diz3UWE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_MgRB7Rq3fCYyolKa0i76tMEn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Insert a one- or two-entry instruction skid buffer between IF and ID. The PC/imem side should continue fetching sequential instructions whenever the buffer has space, while the ID side consumes one buffered instruction only when ID/EX is ready. On redirect, flush the buffer and restart fetch at the EX-resolved target; on imem stalls, hold the outstanding fetch instead of emitting a synthetic NOP into decode. This should overlap random iStall cycles with existing back-end stalls and reduce front-end bubbles while preserving single-retire RVFI ordering and the existing EX-stage control-flow correctness.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 7\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust IF-to-ID bundle comments/types if needed so the payload represents a buffered valid instruction rather than a purely combinational fetch result.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the combinational IF/ID output with a small valid-ready fetch skid buffer that tracks outstanding sequential fetches, flushes on redirect, and only presents valid instructions to decode when available.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Separate front-end fetch backpressure from decode stalls so imem stalls do not force decode bubbles when a buffered instruction is available, while redirects and back-end holds still have priority.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the fetch-buffer availability/consume signals between IF, ID, and hazard logic without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO or RVFI channel-0 retirement contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Insert a one-