{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778680521721,"sessionID":"ses_1de624a85ffeQqxJYJoyypoNcW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_NiueVnHIaHAot0yoPX3bRXpV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\n2: title: \"Load-use MEM bypass\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The previous structural attempts spent LUTs and timing on front-end control-flow machinery, and the log shows those changes either broke correctness or regressed fitness. The current five-stage core still has the classic one-cycle load-use interlock even though the benchmark memory is zero-wait in FPGA and only randomly stalled in cosim. CoreMark has frequent dependent loads through pointer-heavy list, matrix, and state code, so removing this bubble can improve iterations per cycle without adding predictor target adders to the fetch critical path.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Add a MEM-to-EX load-data bypass path that lets an instruction immediately behind a load proceed into EX when the load is in MEM and dmem is ready. Compute the existing load extraction result combinationally in MEM, expose it to the forwarding network, and add a forwarding select for EX operands that chooses the current MEM load result over the older EX/MEM ALU address. Keep the load-use stall only when the load will not have valid data that cycle, such as a dmem stall or a misaligned/trapping load. This structural bypass should remove many single-cycle bubbles while preserving the NRET=1 retirement boundary and RVFI order at MEM/WB.\n8: expected_impact:\n9:   fitness_delta_pct: 6\n10:   confidence: medium\n11: changes:\n12:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n13:     description: \"Add a forwarding select value or metadata needed to distinguish current MEM load-data bypass from ordinary EX/MEM ALU-result forwarding.\"\n14:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n15:     description: \"Expose the combinational, sign-extended load result and load-valid status for the instruction currently in MEM while keeping MEM/WB/RVFI behavior unchanged.\"\n16:   - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n17:     description: \"Prefer the MEM-stage load-data bypass for a dependent consumer when EX/MEM holds a ready load, otherwise keep the existing EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding priorities.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n19:     description: \"Add an operand mux input for the MEM-stage load bypass result so immediate load consumers can execute without waiting for MEM/WB.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n21:     description: \"Relax the load-use interlock when the load in EX/MEM can provide ready MEM-stage data to EX, but retain stalls for dmem backpressure and trapping/misaligned memory operations.\"\n22:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n23:     description: \"Wire the MEM-stage bypass value and readiness signals through the forwarding and EX-stage datapath without changing the core top-level IO or RVFI port set.\"\n\n(End of file - total 23 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\ntitle: \"Load-use MEM bypass\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The previous structural attempts spent LUTs and timing on front-end control-flow machinery, and the log shows those changes either broke correctness or regressed fitness. The current five-stage core still has the classic one-cycle load-use interlock even though the benchmark memory is zero-wait in FPGA and only randomly stalled in cosim. CoreMark has frequent dependent loads through pointer-heavy list, matrix, and state code, so removing this bubble can improve iterations per cycle without adding predictor target adders to the fetch critical path.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a MEM-to-EX load-data bypass path that lets an instruction immediately behind a load proceed into EX when the load is in MEM and dmem is ready. Compute the existing load extraction result combinationally in MEM, expose it to the forwarding network, and add a forwarding select for EX operands that chooses the current MEM load result over the older EX/MEM ALU address. Keep the load-use stall only when the load will not have valid data that cycle, such as a dmem stall or a misaligned/trapping load. This structural bypass should remove many single-cycle bubbles while preserving the NRET=1 retirement boundary and RVFI order at MEM/WB.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add a forwarding select value or metadata needed to distinguish current MEM load-data bypass from ordinary EX/MEM ALU-result forwarding.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Expose the combinational, sign-extended load result and load-valid status for the instruction currently in MEM while keeping MEM/WB/RVFI behavior unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n    description: \"Prefer the MEM-stage load-data bypass for a dependent consumer when EX/MEM holds a ready load, otherwise keep the existing EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding priorities.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add an operand mux input for the MEM-stage load bypass result so immediate load consumers can execute without waiting for MEM/WB.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778680521713,"end":1778680521720}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0ea1979a462cf54d016a0482c82d1081999a16577175e849ed"}},"id":"prt_e219ede640018O2T3WIdG7wznx","sessionID":"ses_1de624a85ffeQqxJYJoyypoNcW","messageID":"msg_e219ecd0a0017hgVZXYKSuW4Vh"}}
