{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684918260,"sessionID":"ses_1de1f19aaffeftqYOGcZLT0vo0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_vkap3pBunN8lU7LOxNlSPB73","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Ordered one-entry store buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts spent timing and LUTs on the front end or on load\n+  bypass paths, and those changes either regressed fitness or broke stall\n+  handling. The current core still freezes the entire pipeline whenever a store\n+  reaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, even though independent ALU, branch, and\n+  register-only instructions behind that store could execute while the store is\n+  waiting. CoreMark has frequent data stores and the apples-to-apples cosim\n+  injects random dmem stalls, so store backpressure is a promising structural\n+  target that avoids fetch-path target adders and load-result critical muxes.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry ordered store buffer at the MEM boundary. A regular data\n+  store can retire into the buffer with its address, byte mask, write data, and\n+  RVFI metadata captured, allowing the front of the pipeline to keep executing\n+  non-memory instructions while the buffer drives dmem until dmem_ready accepts\n+  the write. Preserve precise in-order behavior by stalling any younger load,\n+  store, MMIO access, FENCE, EBREAK, or illegal/trapping instruction until the\n+  buffer drains; MMIO marker/UART stores should bypass the buffer and keep the\n+  existing blocking behavior so CoreMark timing brackets remain exact. This\n+  should recover cycles lost to random store stalls with modest control and no\n+  new IF critical-path logic.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add minimal store-buffer payload typing or MEM-stage metadata fields needed to capture a committed regular store without changing the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement the one-entry ordered store buffer, keep MMIO/trapping stores blocking, and expose buffer-full/drain status for pipeline backpressure.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Stall younger memory, MMIO, fence, halt, and trapping operations while a buffered store is pending, but allow independent non-memory instructions to proceed.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status and younger-instruction qualifiers between MEM, hazard detection, and the existing single-channel RVFI retirement path.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Ordered one-entry store buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts spent timing and LUTs on the front end or on load\n+  bypass paths, and those changes either regressed fitness or broke stall\n+  handling. The current core still freezes the entire pipeline whenever a store\n+  reaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, even though independent ALU, branch, and\n+  register-only instructions behind that store could execute while the store is\n+  waiting. CoreMark has frequent data stores and the apples-to-apples cosim\n+  injects random dmem stalls, so store backpressure is a promising structural\n+  target that avoids fetch-path target adders and load-result critical muxes.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry ordered store buffer at the MEM boundary. A regular data\n+  store can retire into the buffer with its address, byte mask, write data, and\n+  RVFI metadata captured, allowing the front of the pipeline to keep executing\n+  non-memory instructions while the buffer drives dmem until dmem_ready accepts\n+  the write. Preserve precise in-order behavior by stalling any younger load,\n+  store, MMIO access, FENCE, EBREAK, or illegal/trapping instruction until the\n+  buffer drains; MMIO marker/UART stores should bypass the buffer and keep the\n+  existing blocking behavior so CoreMark timing brackets remain exact. This\n+  should recover cycles lost to random store stalls with modest control and no\n+  new IF critical-path logic.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add minimal store-buffer payload typing or MEM-stage metadata fields needed to capture a committed regular store without changing the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement the one-entry ordered store buffer, keep MMIO/trapping stores blocking, and expose buffer-full/drain status for pipeline backpressure.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Stall younger memory, MMIO, fence, halt, and trapping operations while a buffered store is pending, but allow independent non-memory instructions to proceed.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status and younger-instruction qualifiers between MEM, hazard detection, and the existing single-channel RVFI retirement path.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml