{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778687378209,"sessionID":"ses_1ddf9c25cffezPuCxxaEhdOvsr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_t8bNP9v99PaaQfQq4JUxisLw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Pipeline EX operand retiming\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added fetch prediction, skid buffering, load bypassing,\n+  or store buffering all paid too much control-path cost. The current core's remaining\n+  high-fanout structural path is more basic: ID/EX values pass through forwarding muxes,\n+  ALU operand selection, ALU or branch compare/target logic, and into EX/MEM plus the\n+  redirect path in one cycle. Retiming that boundary can target Fmax without adding a\n+  predictor, memory ordering structure, or RVFI contract change.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split the existing EX stage into a lightweight EX1 operand/metadata register and an EX2\n+  execute/redirect stage. EX1 captures the forwarded rs1/rs2 values, selected ALU operands,\n+  decoded control, immediate, PC, and RVFI source data; EX2 performs the ALU operation,\n+  branch/jump resolution, M-unit handshake, and drives the existing EX/MEM payload. Add the\n+  minimal hazard/forwarding adjustments needed for the extra execute stage, preferring a\n+  one-cycle interlock on immediately dependent ALU consumers over wide new bypass muxes if\n+  that keeps timing short. This structural retiming should shorten the common forwarding-to-\n+  ALU-to-EX/MEM cone and may raise Tang Nano 20K Fmax enough to offset a small CPI cost,\n+  while preserving NRET=1 retirement at MEM/WB and all RVFI ordering/trap behavior.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX1/EX2 pipeline bundle carrying forwarded operands, selected ALU inputs, decoded control, PC, instruction, and RVFI source metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Retiming split: register forwarded operands in EX1, move ALU/branch/M-unit execution to EX2, and emit the same EX/MEM payload and redirect signals from EX2.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Account for the added execute stage by stalling or bubbling only the producer-consumer cases that cannot be safely forwarded after retiming.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Update forwarding source priorities for the retimed execute boundary without adding a MEM-load bypass path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire any new EX-stage stall, bubble, and forwarding signals while keeping the existing NRET=1 top-level IO and MEM/WB RVFI retirement boundary unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Pipeline EX operand retiming\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added fetch prediction, skid buffering, load bypassing,\n+  or store buffering all paid too much control-path cost. The current core's remaining\n+  high-fanout structural path is more basic: ID/EX values pass through forwarding muxes,\n+  ALU operand selection, ALU or branch compare/target logic, and into EX/MEM plus the\n+  redirect path in one cycle. Retiming that boundary can target Fmax without adding a\n+  predictor, memory ordering structure, or RVFI contract change.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split the existing EX stage into a lightweight EX1 operand/metadata register and an EX2\n+  execute/redirect stage. EX1 captures the forwarded rs1/rs2 values, selected ALU operands,\n+  decoded control, immediate, PC, and RVFI source data; EX2 performs the ALU operation,\n+  branch/jump resolution, M-unit handshake, and drives the existing EX/MEM payload. Add the\n+  minimal hazard/forwarding adjustments needed for the extra execute stage, preferring a\n+  one-cycle interlock on immediately dependent ALU consumers over wide new bypass muxes if\n+  that keeps timing short. This structural retiming should shorten the common forwarding-to-\n+  ALU-to-EX/MEM cone and may raise Tang Nano 20K Fmax enough to offset a small CPI cost,\n+  while preserving NRET=1 retirement at MEM/WB and all RVFI ordering/trap behavior.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX1/EX2 pipeline bundle carrying forwarded operands, selected ALU inputs, decoded control, PC, instruction, and RVFI source metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Retiming split: register forwarded operands in EX1, move ALU/branch/M-unit execution to EX2, and emit the same EX/MEM payload and redirect signals from EX2.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Account for the added execute stage by stalling or bubbling only the producer-consumer cases that cannot be safely forwarded after retiming.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Update forwarding source priorities for the retimed execute boundary without adding a MEM-load bypass path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire any new EX-stage stall, bubble, and forwarding signals while keeping the existing NRET=1 top-level IO and MEM/WB RVFI retirement boundary unchanged.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Pipeline EX operand retiming\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added fetch prediction, skid buffering, load bypassing,\n+  or store buffering all paid too much control-path cost. The current core's remaining\n+  high-fanout structural path is more basic: ID/EX values pass through forwarding muxes,\n+  ALU operand selection, ALU or branch compare/target logic, and into EX/MEM plus the\n+  redirect path in one cycle. Retiming that boundary can target Fmax without adding a\n+  predictor, memory ordering structure, or RVFI contract change.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split the existing EX stage into a lightweight EX1 operand/metadata register and an EX2\n+  execute/redirect stage. EX1 captures the forwarded rs1/rs2 values, selected ALU operands,\n+  decoded control, immediate, PC, and RVFI source data; EX2 performs the ALU operation,\n+  branch/jump resolution, M-unit handshake, and drives the existing EX/MEM payload. Add the\n+  minimal hazard/forwarding adjustments needed for the extra execute stage, preferring a\n+  one-cycle interlock on immediately dependent ALU consumers over wide new bypass muxes if\n+  that keeps timing short. This structural retiming should shorten the common forwarding-to-\n+  ALU-to-EX/MEM cone and may raise Tang Nano 20K Fmax enough to offset a small CPI cost,\n+  while preserving NRET=1 retirement at MEM/WB and all RVFI ordering/trap behavior.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX1/EX2 pipeline bundle carrying forwarded operands, selected ALU inputs, decoded control, PC, instruction, and RVFI source metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Retiming split: register forwarded operands in EX1, move ALU/branch/M-unit execution to EX2, and emit the same EX/MEM payload and redirect signals from EX2.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Account for the added execute stage by stalling or bubbling only the producer-consumer cases that cannot be safely forwarded after retiming.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Update forwarding source priorities for the retimed execute boundary without adding a MEM-load bypass path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire any new EX-stage stall, bubble, and forwarding signals while keeping the existing NRET=1 top-level IO and MEM/WB RVFI retirement boundary unchanged.\"\n","additions":34,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778687378205,"end":1778687378208}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_01b83db06b19bd7b016a049d78bafc8198abdcaec1628c4c76"}},"id":"prt_e22071ffb00124Lj0i3RiqETbY","sessionID":"ses_1ddf9c25cffezPuCxxaEhdOvsr","messageID":"msg_e22070be20010XExbsfFNFiB6N"}}
