{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778689165329,"sessionID":"ses_1ddde3ef1ffelGBZQCOkrNjfqc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_cUEm7VQGSVx3D0zs8Q1BmQVZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Register dmem stall boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts added front-end prediction, fetch buffering, load\n+  bypassing, store buffering, or a deeper EX pipe, and each paid too much in\n+  mux/control cost or correctness complexity. A smaller structural target is\n+  the current dmem stall path: io_dmemReady fans combinationally through the\n+  hazard unit into PC hold, ID hold, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB valid clearing in\n+  the same cycle. CoreMark's apples-to-apples mode injects random dmem stalls,\n+  so this control path is active during evaluation, and reducing its fanout may\n+  improve Fmax without changing the visible memory ordering contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-cycle registered MEM busy/accepted boundary for data-memory\n+  operations. When a load or store enters MEM, capture whether it is waiting for\n+  dmem_ready in a small state bit local to the MEM/hazard interface; while that\n+  bit is set, hold EX/MEM and clear MEM/WB valid exactly as today, but drive the\n+  global pipeline stalls from the registered busy state rather than directly\n+  from io_dmemReady. Keep dmem_addr, dmem_wdata, dmem_wen, dmem_ren, RVFI memory\n+  masks/data, misalignment traps, and all in-order retirement behavior\n+  unchanged. This deliberately accepts at most one extra cycle on the first\n+  stalled memory access in exchange for shortening high-fanout ready-to-control\n+  timing, with no predictor metadata, no load bypass mux, and no store ordering\n+  relaxation.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the direct io_dmemReady hazard input with a registered MEM-wait signal while preserving the NRET=1 RVFI port set and existing dmem port wiring.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Drive dmem stall decisions from the registered MEM-wait state instead of combinational io_dmemReady fanout, keeping existing imem, redirect, load-use, and M-unit priorities.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add the local one-bit memory-wait/accepted tracking needed to hold a memory op until dmem_ready while keeping MEM/WB valid clearing and RVFI memory fields equivalent.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Register dmem stall boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts added front-end prediction, fetch buffering, load\n+  bypassing, store buffering, or a deeper EX pipe, and each paid too much in\n+  mux/control cost or correctness complexity. A smaller structural target is\n+  the current dmem stall path: io_dmemReady fans combinationally through the\n+  hazard unit into PC hold, ID hold, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB valid clearing in\n+  the same cycle. CoreMark's apples-to-apples mode injects random dmem stalls,\n+  so this control path is active during evaluation, and reducing its fanout may\n+  improve Fmax without changing the visible memory ordering contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-cycle registered MEM busy/accepted boundary for data-memory\n+  operations. When a load or store enters MEM, capture whether it is waiting for\n+  dmem_ready in a small state bit local to the MEM/hazard interface; while that\n+  bit is set, hold EX/MEM and clear MEM/WB valid exactly as today, but drive the\n+  global pipeline stalls from the registered busy state rather than directly\n+  from io_dmemReady. Keep dmem_addr, dmem_wdata, dmem_wen, dmem_ren, RVFI memory\n+  masks/data, misalignment traps, and all in-order retirement behavior\n+  unchanged. This deliberately accepts at most one extra cycle on the first\n+  stalled memory access in exchange for shortening high-fanout ready-to-control\n+  timing, with no predictor metadata, no load bypass mux, and no store ordering\n+  relaxation.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the direct io_dmemReady hazard input with a registered MEM-wait signal while preserving the NRET=1 RVFI port set and existing dmem port wiring.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Drive dmem stall decisions from the registered MEM-wait state instead of combinational io_dmemReady fanout, keeping existing imem, redirect, load-use, and M-unit priorities.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add the local one-bit memory-wait/accepted tracking needed to hold a memory op until dmem_ready while keeping MEM/WB valid clearing and RVFI memory fields equivalent.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Register dmem stall boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts added front-end prediction, fetch buffering, load\n+  bypassing, store buffering, or a deeper EX pipe, and each paid too much in\n+  mux/control cost or correctness complexity. A smaller structural target is\n+  the current dmem stall path: io_dmemReady fans combinationally through the\n+  hazard unit into PC hold, ID hold, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB valid clearing in\n+  the same cycle. CoreMark's apples-to-apples mode injects random dmem stalls,\n+  so this control path is active during evaluation, and reducing its fanout may\n+  improve Fmax without changing the visible memory ordering contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-cycle registered MEM busy/accepted boundary for data-memory\n+  operations. When a load or store enters MEM, capture whether it is waiting for\n+  dmem_ready in a small state bit local to the MEM/hazard interface; while that\n+  bit is set, hold EX/MEM and clear MEM/WB valid exactly as today, but drive the\n+  global pipeline stalls from the registered busy state rather than directly\n+  from io_dmemReady. Keep dmem_addr, dmem_wdata, dmem_wen, dmem_ren, RVFI memory\n+  masks/data, misalignment traps, and all in-order retirement behavior\n+  unchanged. This deliberately accepts at most one extra cycle on the first\n+  stalled memory access in exchange for shortening high-fanout ready-to-control\n+  timing, with no predictor metadata, no load bypass mux, and no store ordering\n+  relaxation.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the direct io_dmemReady hazard input with a registered MEM-wait signal while preserving the NRET=1 RVFI port set and existing dmem port wiring.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Drive dmem stall decisions from the registered MEM-wait state instead of combinational io_dmemReady fanout, keeping existing imem, redirect, load-use, and M-unit priorities.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add the local one-bit memory-wait/accepted tracking needed to hold a memory op until dmem_ready while keeping MEM/WB valid clearing and RVFI memory fields equivalent.\"\n","additions":34,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778689165323,"end":1778689165328}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00aae4e0d199aeff016a04a475904c81999ba428827a64dbcf"}},"id":"prt_e22226ba2001iWY01UB1TgG930","sessionID":"ses_1ddde3ef1ffelGBZQCOkrNjfqc","messageID":"msg_e222263970019EpyCcqX1bnxSr"}}
