{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778680456179,"sessionID":"ses_1de624aedffeUTdz1TO7ZXsmCS","part":{"id":"prt_e219de3f2001tV0399hQD0iix3","messageID":"msg_e219dddfe001vmyeqQvdjrfudA","sessionID":"ses_1de624aedffeUTdz1TO7ZXsmCS","snapshot":"d477ce5096c201a9bdb9c65ac39195d8d680cc62","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778680462685,"sessionID":"ses_1de624aedffeUTdz1TO7ZXsmCS","part":{"id":"prt_e219dfc5a001ocFsF9bJwKJyXq","messageID":"msg_e219dddfe001vmyeqQvdjrfudA","sessionID":"ses_1de624aedffeUTdz1TO7ZXsmCS","type":"text","text":"Prior predictor attempts failed by adding target decode/muxing on the fetch path. I’m going to propose a lower-risk predictor that changes only redirect policy for unconditional PC-relative jumps, avoiding branch target prediction and RAS logic.","time":{"start":1778680462426,"end":1778680462684},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0a9936174f49841f016a04828e3304819b97fb94afc0b2b86e","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778680463082,"sessionID":"ses_1de624aedffeUTdz1TO7ZXsmCS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_zlt5hSOxY0vjM9TxiZgt7UKi","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":4,"limit":4},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFNT branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an IF-stage static backward-taken/forward-not-taken predictor using the fetched instruction bits to compute B-type targets for negative branch immediates, and optionally early-predict JAL targets because they are unconditional PC-relative redirects. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction; mispredicted forward-taken branches, not-taken backward branches, and JALR still recover through the existing flush path. This should remove most loop-closing branch bubbles while preserving the single-retire RVFI contract because retirement remains unchanged at MEM/WB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles with the predicted next PC needed for EX-stage mispredict detection.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement static BTFNT next-PC selection for backward conditional branches and early PC-relative JAL prediction from fetched instruction bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Lat... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Simplify MEM load lane muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte-lane handling as explicit case muxes keyed by addr[1:0] instead of expressions like dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0] * 8) and mask << addr[1:0]. Keep the same misalignment trap behavior, RVFI aligned mem_addr reporting, replicated store data convention, and MEM/WB retirement boundary. This should reduce LUT depth and routing on the common load-data path while preserving the existing five-stage control flow and single-retire NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load-data shifts and shifted byte masks with explicit addr[1:0] case muxes for LB/LBU/LH/LHU/LW and store masks.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a one- or two-entry instruction skid buffer between IF and ID. The PC/imem side should continue fetching sequential instructions whenever the buffer has space, while the ID side consumes one buffered instruction only when ID/EX is ready. On redirect, flush the buffer and restart fetch at the EX-resolved target; on imem stalls, hold the outstanding fetch instead of emitting a synthetic NOP into decode. This should overlap random iStall cycles with existing back-end stalls and reduce front-end bubbles while preserving single-retire RVFI ordering and the existing EX-stage control-flow correctness.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"descr... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny return-address stack predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small 4-entry return-address stack that predicts only canonical returns\\n(JALR x0, 0(x1/x5)) in IF. Push pc+4 for link-register calls when they resolve,\\npop/predict the stack top for returns, and carry the predicted next PC through the\\npipeline so EX redirects only on mismatch. This keeps ordinary branch fetch as pc+4,\\navoids B-type immediate decode and target adders in the IF critical path, and should\\nrecover part of the call/return control-flow penalty with modest LUT/FF cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC and return-predicted metadata to IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM bundles for mispredict detection and RAS bookkeeping.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect canonical return encodings in the fetched instruction and select the RAS top as the next PC only when the stack is nonempty.... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 7 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFNT branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an IF-stage static backward-taken/forward-not-taken predictor using the fetched instruction bits to compute B-type targets for negative branch immediates, and optionally early-predict JAL targets because they are unconditional PC-relative redirects. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction; mispredicted forward-taken branches, not-taken backward branches, and JALR still recover through the existing flush path. This should remove most loop-closing branch bubbles while preserving the single-retire RVFI contract because retirement remains unchanged at MEM/WB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles with the predicted next PC needed for EX-stage mispredict detection.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement static BTFNT next-PC selection for backward conditional branches and early PC-relative JAL prediction from fetched instruction bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Lat... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Simplify MEM load lane muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After the successful M-unit split, the remaining always-active timing paths are more likely to be ordinary RV32I datapath logic than rare multiply/divide arithmetic. The MEM stage currently uses variable shifts for load extraction and shifted masks for byte lanes, which can synthesize into wider mux/barrel-shifter logic on the FPGA load-to-WB path. CoreMark performs many byte, halfword, and word accesses, so a smaller MEM-stage cone should improve Fmax without changing CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte-lane handling as explicit case muxes keyed by addr[1:0] instead of expressions like dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0] * 8) and mask << addr[1:0]. Keep the same misalignment trap behavior, RVFI aligned mem_addr reporting, replicated store data convention, and MEM/WB retirement boundary. This should reduce LUT depth and routing on the common load-data path while preserving the existing five-stage control flow and single-retire NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load-data shifts and shifted byte masks with explicit addr[1:0] case muxes for LB/LBU/LH/LHU/LW and store masks.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a one- or two-entry instruction skid buffer between IF and ID. The PC/imem side should continue fetching sequential instructions whenever the buffer has space, while the ID side consumes one buffered instruction only when ID/EX is ready. On redirect, flush the buffer and restart fetch at the EX-resolved target; on imem stalls, hold the outstanding fetch instead of emitting a synthetic NOP into decode. This should overlap random iStall cycles with existing back-end stalls and reduce front-end bubbles while preserving single-retire RVFI ordering and the existing EX-stage control-flow correctness.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"descr... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny return-address stack predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small 4-entry return-address stack that predicts only canonical returns\\n(JALR x0, 0(x1/x5)) in IF. Push pc+4 for link-register calls when they resolve,\\npop/predict the stack top for returns, and carry the predicted next PC through the\\npipeline so EX redirects only on mismatch. This keeps ordinary branch fetch as pc+4,\\navoids B-type immediate decode and target adders in the IF critical path, and should\\nrecover part of the call/return control-flow penalty with modest LUT/FF cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC and return-predicted metadata to IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM bundles for mispredict detection and RAS bookkeeping.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect canonical return encodings in the fetched instruction and select the RAS top as the next PC only when the stack is nonempty.... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778680463079,"end":1778680463081}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0a9936174f49841f016a04828e6b94819bbb2e0163ea7ac007"}},"id":"prt_e219dfd5d0013VUCpc4LnFQYuB","sessionID":"ses_1de624aedffeUTdz1TO7ZXsmCS","messageID":"msg_e219dddfe001vmyeqQvdjrfudA"}}
