{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684861860,"sessionID":"ses_1de1f1a2fffeDc6ylGcZER8Nlw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_PJIbpO4TTmMMdk6xN72loOi6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"predictor|branch|BTB|BTFNT|JAL|RAS|return|target|redirect","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 11 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Multicycle RV32M arithmetic unit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU computes every multiply and divide result combinationally in\\nthe EX stage, including signed and unsigned 64-bit products plus divider and\\nremainder operators. That wide arithmetic cone is a likely Fmax limiter on\\nTang Nano 20K, while CoreMark's hot path should not need single-cycle DIV/REM\\nthroughput. Trading rare M-extension latency for a shorter common EX critical\\npath should improve iterations/second through higher clock frequency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU computes every multiply and divide result combinationally in\\nthe EX stage, including signed and unsigned 64-bit products plus divider and\\nremainder operators. That wide arithmetic cone is a likely Fmax limiter on\\nTang Nano 20K, while CoreMark's hot path should not need single-cycle DIV/REM\\nthroughput. Trading rare M-extension latency for a shorter common EX critical\\npath should improve iterations/second through higher clock frequency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M operations out of the always-combinational ALU path behind a\\nsmall multicycle M-unit handshake in EX. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/branch/address\\noperations purely combinational, but when the decoded alu_op is MUL/DIV/REM,\\nhold ID/EX and EX/MEM until the iterative arithmetic result is ready, then\\nretire normally through the existing MEM/WB and RVFI path. This should remove\\ndivider and large multiplier logic from the ordinary EX-stage timing path;\\nthe added stalls only affect uncommon M instructions and should be outweighed\\nby improved Fmax on the FPGA fitness metric.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Restrict the combinational ALU to fast RV32I operations and expose only lightweight M-op selection or helper logic needed by the new M-unit.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a multicycl...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve control flow in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark spends a significant fraction of its bracketed runtime in tight loops and conditional control flow. The current five-stage pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX, then flushes both IF and ID, so every taken branch or jump pays roughly a two-cycle redirect penalty. Reducing that penalty improves iterations/cycle without increasing retirement width or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark spends a significant fraction of its bracketed runtime in tight loops and conditional control flow. The current five-stage pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX, then flushes both IF and ID, so every taken branch or jump pays roughly a two-cycle redirect penalty. Reducing that penalty improves iterations/cycle without increasing retirement width or touching the external NRET=1 contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move branch and JAL/JALR target/condition resolution from EX into the decode stage, with decode-stage operand forwarding from EX/MEM and MEM/WB for branch compares and JALR base operands. Keep the existing EX-stage trap/metadata path as the retirement source, but let ID drive redirect one cycle earlier when operands are available; stall only for unresolved load-to-branch/JALR dependencies. This should cut the common taken-control penalty from two bubbles to one while preserving RVFI order, trap reporting, and single-channel retirement.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ID-stage early redirect signals into the IF and hazard path while preserving the existing NRET=1 RVFI port set.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add early branch/JAL/JALR resolution using decoded control, immediates, regfile operands, and forwarded compare/base operands.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend forwarding ...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFNT branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches sequentially and resolves every branch or jump in EX, so each taken loop branch pays a two-instruction front-end flush. CoreMark has tight loops and many backward branches, making a small static predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without adding much FPGA area or hurting the ALU critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an IF-stage static backward-taken/forward-not-taken predictor using the fetched instruction bits to compute B-type targets for negative branch immediates, and optionally early-predict JAL targets because they are unconditional PC-relative redirects. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction; mispredicted forward-taken branches, not-taken backward branches, and JALR still recover through the existing flush path. This should remove most loop-closing branch bubbles while preserving the single-retire RVFI contract because retirement remains unchanged at MEM/WB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles with the predicted next PC needed for EX-stage mispredict detection.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement static BTFNT next-PC selection for backward conditional branches and early PC-relative JAL prediction from fetched instruction bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Lat...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID storage: the IF payload is combinational from the current PC and imem data, and an imem-not-ready cycle injects a bubble directly into decode. With the tournament cosim using roughly 22% random instruction stalls, CoreMark loses many cycles even when the back end is already stalled by load-use, dmem, or the multicycle M unit. A small fetch buffer is a structural way to recover iterations/cycle without revisiting the prior broken ID-stage branch-resolution path or adding fetch-path target adders that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a one- or two-entry instruction skid buffer between IF and ID. The PC/imem side should continue fetching sequential instructions whenever the buffer has space, while the ID side consumes one buffered instruction only when ID/EX is ready. On redirect, flush the buffer and restart fetch at the EX-resolved target; on imem stalls, hold the outstanding fetch instead of emitting a synthetic NOP into decode. This should overlap random iStall cycles with existing back-end stalls and reduce front-end bubbles while preserving single-retire RVFI ordering and the existing EX-stage control-flow correctness.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"descr...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny return-address stack predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The prior static BTFNT predictor targeted loop branches but put branch immediate decode\\nand target adders directly on the IF PC-update path, regressing the CoreMark fitness\\ndespite saving some bubbles. CoreMark still has frequent function calls and returns,\\nand the current core pays the same EX-stage redirect penalty for every JALR return.\\nA tiny return predictor can attack those bubbles without adding branch-target arithmetic\\nto fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small 4-entry return-address stack that predicts only canonical returns\\n(JALR x0, 0(x1/x5)) in IF. Push pc+4 for link-register calls when they resolve,\\npop/predict the stack top for returns, and carry the predicted next PC through the\\npipeline so EX redirects only on mismatch. This keeps ordinary branch fetch as pc+4,\\navoids B-type immediate decode and target adders in the IF critical path, and should\\nrecover part of the call/return control-flow penalty with modest LUT/FF cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC and return-predicted metadata to IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM bundles for mispredict detection and RAS bookkeeping.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect canonical return encodings in the fetched instruction and select the RAS top as the next PC only when the stack is nonempty....\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against the\\nraw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction, regardless of whether\\nthat instruction actually consumes those operands. For I-type immediates,\\nloads, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK, some of those fields are\\nimmediates or destination bits rather than true sources. Any accidental match\\nwith the preceding load rd inserts an unnecessary bubble, directly reducing\\nCoreMark iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against the\\nraw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction, regardless of whether\\nthat instruction actually consumes those operands. For I-type immediates,\\nloads, JALR, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK, some of those fields are\\nimmediates or destination bits rather than true sources. Any accidental match\\nwith the preceding load rd inserts an unnecessary bubble, directly reducing\\nCoreMark iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Make the load-use interlock source-aware by qualifying the rd comparisons with\\nsimple decoded uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 signals for the instruction currently in\\nIF/ID. Keep the existing one-cycle stall for real load consumers, but avoid\\nstalling on unused source fields such as OP-IMM rs2 bits, U/J-type operand\\nfields, and SYSTEM/FENCE encodings. This should improve CPI under CoreMark's\\nload-heavy code while adding only small opcode decode logic off the main ALU\\nand memory datapaths, so Fmax should be largely preserved.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive or wire IF/ID source-use qualifiers into the hazard unit without changing the NRET=1 top-level RVFI interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Load-use MEM bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The previous structural attempts spent LUTs and timing on front-end control-flow machinery, and the log shows those changes either broke correctness or regressed fitness. The current five-stage core still has the classic one-cycle load-use interlock even though the benchmark memory is zero-wait in FPGA and only randomly stalled in cosim. CoreMark has frequent dependent loads through pointer-heavy list, matrix, and state code, so removing this bubble can improve iterations per cycle without adding predictor target adders to the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The previous structural attempts spent LUTs and timing on front-end control-flow machinery, and the log shows those changes either broke correctness or regressed fitness. The current five-stage core still has the classic one-cycle load-use interlock even though the benchmark memory is zero-wait in FPGA and only randomly stalled in cosim. CoreMark has frequent dependent loads through pointer-heavy list, matrix, and state code, so removing this bubble can improve iterations per cycle without adding predictor target adders to the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a MEM-to-EX load-data bypass path that lets an instruction immediately behind a load proceed into EX when the load is in MEM and dmem is ready. Compute the existing load extraction result combinationally in MEM, expose it to the forwarding network, and add a forwarding select for EX operands that chooses the current MEM load result over the older EX/MEM ALU address. Keep the load-use stall only when the load will not have valid data that cycle, such as a dmem stall or a misaligned/trapping load. This structural bypass should remove many single-cycle bubbles while preserving the NRET=1 retirement boundary and RVFI order at MEM/WB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\"...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Decode-stage JAL predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The prior predictor attempts regressed because they placed branch target decode,\\ntarget adders, return detection, and prediction muxes directly on the IF PC path.\\nCoreMark still pays the existing EX redirect penalty for every unconditional JAL,\\nand JAL targets are PC-relative with no register dependency or branch condition.\\nPredicting only JAL in decode should recover one control-flow bubble for calls and\\nlong jumps while avoiding the risky fetch-path predictor logic that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The prior predictor attempts regressed because they placed branch target decode,\\ntarget adders, return detection, and prediction muxes directly on the IF PC path.\\nCoreMark still pays the existing EX redirect penalty for every unconditional JAL,\\nand JAL targets are PC-relative with no register dependency or branch condition.\\nPredicting only JAL in decode should recover one control-flow bubble for calls and\\nlong jumps while avoiding the risky fetch-path predictor logic that hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a narrow decode-stage always-taken predictor for legal JAL instructions only.\\nID computes pc+imm for JAL, redirects fetch one cycle before EX would, and records\\nthe predicted next PC in the ID/EX bundle. EX then suppresses the normal JAL redirect\\nwhen the resolved jump target matches the predicted target, but retains the existing\\nEX recovery path for conditional branches, JALR, illegal instructions, and any target\\nmismatch. Because the predictor excludes branches and returns, it needs no B-type\\nimmediate decode in IF, no RAS state, and no operand forwarding, making it a smaller\\npredictor angle with a better chance of improving CoreMark iterations/cycle without\\nsacrificing the current high Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add p...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Source-qualified load interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\\nsource bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\\narchitecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\\ninstructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\\niterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector compares the preceding load rd against both raw\\nsource bitfields of the following instruction, even when those bits are not\\narchitecturally consumed. CoreMark has many loads and immediate/control\\ninstructions, so accidental rd matches can inject bubbles that reduce\\niterations per cycle without protecting any real dependency.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny source-use decode for the IF/ID instruction and qualify the existing\\nload-use interlock with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. This is a narrower retry of the\\nearlier source-aware load-use idea: do not mask or reinterpret RVFI operand\\nreporting, and do not add MEM bypass selects or fetch prediction paths. The\\ncore should keep the one-cycle stall for true load consumers while avoiding\\nfalse stalls on OP-IMM rs2 fields, U/J-type immediates, FENCE, SYSTEM/EBREAK,\\nand other instructions that do not read both source registers.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive simple IF/ID uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 qualifiers from opcode/funct class and pass them only to the hazard unit.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate load-use rd comparisons with the source-use qualifiers while preserving existing dmem, imem, redirect, and M-unit stall priority.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive simple IF/ID use...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register IF/ID fetch boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end feeds imem_data directly through decode, immediate\\ngeneration, regfile address decode, hazard checks, and into the ID/EX\\nregister in a single cycle. Prior structural attempts tried to hide stalls or\\nreduce bubbles with added prediction and bypass control, but those changes\\nregressed by lengthening already sensitive mux/control paths. A real IF/ID\\nregister is a simpler structural retiming that targets Fmax directly.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end feeds imem_data directly through decode, immediate\\ngeneration, regfile address decode, hazard checks, and into the ID/EX\\nregister in a single cycle. Prior structural attempts tried to hide stalls or\\nreduce bubbles with added prediction and bypass control, but those changes\\nregressed by lengthening already sensitive mux/control paths. A real IF/ID\\nregister is a simpler structural retiming that targets Fmax directly.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a proper IF/ID pipeline register inside the fetch stage, so fetched\\ninstruction, PC, and valid are captured before decode sees them. The PC still\\nadvances only when the downstream ID stage can accept the entry, and redirect\\nflushes the registered IF/ID payload before wrong-path state can retire. This\\nadds one front-end cycle and may slightly increase taken-control penalty, but\\nit removes the imem-to-decoder combinational path and should improve FPGA\\nFmax enough to raise CoreMark iter/sec without changing the NRET=1 retirement\\ncontract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep the existing IF/ID bundle shape, but document and use it as a registered pipeline boundary rather than a combinational fetch payload.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an IF/ID register for pc, instruction, and valid; hold it on deco...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny resolved-target BTB\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves all taken branches and jumps in EX, so tight CoreMark loops pay a two-bubble redirect penalty. Prior predictor attempts regressed because they decoded immediates, computed targets, or managed return-stack state on the front-end critical path. A small BTB trained from already-resolved EX redirects can target the same loop bubbles while avoiding fetch-stage target arithmetic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves all taken branches and jumps in EX, so tight CoreMark loops pay a two-bubble redirect penalty. Prior predictor attempts regressed because they decoded immediates, computed targets, or managed return-stack state on the front-end critical path. A small BTB trained from already-resolved EX redirects can target the same loop bubbles while avoiding fetch-stage target arithmetic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped branch target buffer that stores resolved taken conditional-branch targets, preferably only backward loop branches, along with a compact PC tag and a 2-bit confidence counter. IF predicts to the stored target on a tag hit with a taken counter, otherwise it keeps the existing pc+4 path; EX updates the BTB after branch resolution and flushes on any predicted/resolved next-PC mismatch. Because the target is stored from the prior execution, the fetch path adds only a small tag compare and next-PC mux instead of B/J immediate decode and target adders, which should recover loop-closing branch bubbles with less Fmax damage than the previous predictor attempts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Carry predicted next-PC metadata through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX can distinguish correct BTB predictions from mispredictions without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Imple...","metadata":{"matches":11,"truncated":false},"title":"predictor|branch|BTB|BTFNT|JAL|RAS|return|target|redirect","time":{"start":1778684861826,"end":1778684861857}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c958cb7e8947a56016a0493bdac70819bb412c8ad8444073b"}},"id":"prt_e21e11d7e001R65BWl2CsW2eHk","sessionID":"ses_1de1f1a2fffeDc6ylGcZER8Nlw","messageID":"msg_e21e0e6b900155gbTDwcune10W"}}
